description: Beginning  on Draft Root Beer, climb the opening moves. Clip the first bolt and work up and left to an in-cut shelf. Clip the bolt and continue up and straight from here until you reach the anchor.

name: Flying Pig
description: Climb the featured face to a hard roof sequence. Make sure you have an attentive belay

name: Osiris the virus
description: Starting at the low point of a jug rail matched(butt should be on ground) work your way right working the feet to a fairly easy cross. Work feet again an set for a throw then to another. Then traverse right an work your way up the easy face. The finish has good holds but there is some that could be questionable(Use your best judgment). Top out is a right hand up to a horn feature then slide left onto the ledge. Also in the traverse you will encounter two sharp crimps an a crummy slopey pocket. Not sure on the grade. Hopefully others will get on it. If I am not the FA please let me know and we can change it.

name: Von Jakob
description: Climb the face. Traverse right around the roof. Follow easy ground to anchors.

name: The High Pass
description: Make thin moves to easy ground. Climb the steep, juggy roof to high anchors.

name: Road's Closed
description: Start matched on good hold beneath the two big pockets and work up and left to a hang and drop

name: Creekside
description: Fun line. Â Start on shelf and move through pockets, throw for the jug and top out.Â  Rinse and repeat.

name: Wicked Mortals
description: Needs some more cleaning and traffic on the boulder. Then, it will be a classic. Stand start and work straight up using the well-featured holds.

name: Alto standard
description: A neat addition right off the trail.    The obvious line traverses right  through the rail into the pocketed roof section and finishes with a good top out to the right.   It is a very obvious line, so I imagine that it has been climbed before.  Any Route name/ FA info?

name: Bane of Chris
description: Start standing with good holds and a massive pocket for a foot. Then use an undercling to reach up onto bulging face of the boulder and blindly find the crimp. Now match the crimp, hike up your feet, and then toss your left hand up to the ledge at the peak of the arete. Then get your feet up to the crimp and walk off the top.

name: Cat's Paws
description: Start on Kitten's Claws and work right using the underclings and top out on Bane of Chris

name: Cinderella Ate My Daughter
description: Sit start and work up using the variety of well-featured holds.

name: Dream Crusher
description: This is a fun slab problem that starts on two small ledges with tiny variations in the rock for feet. Moving up to a sidepull and then manteling onto the top of the boulder is probably the crux. We climbed it in 90 degree weather. It is probably more of a 2 when it's cold out.

name: Kitten's Claws
description: Start in the big hole near the ground and work straight up using the crack

name: Wet Dream
description: Start matched on a huge ledge with small feet. Then move up and to the right to a crimp and a great jug. Then use another good hold on the top to move up the face.

name: Deer Hunting with Jesus
description: Low sit start. Start on left side crimps and move up right toward lip.

name: Road Trip Rwanda
description: Stand start and work up.

name: Dog Fight
description: Start on high edges and pull a difficult move to shelf above.

name: Jimbo's
description: Starting standing on good holds, move upwards to a big cruxy huck to a nice sandstone sloper. Top out the boulder. The classic warm up of the Beach. Awesome, overhanging sandstone action.

name: Mark's Arete
description: There are a lot of holds on the arete, so the beta can be hard to read. There are a couple variations on the problem, but I began the problem starting on two holds on opposite sides of the arete, doing a big move up and left. A couple more weird slopey moves will put you on top. Not the best problem at the Beach, but not bad either.

name: Mary's First Time
description: Proud Mary/Sex on the Beach link-up. Start on Mary, do some moves to gain the jug of Sex, finish on that. Found this on a local guy's 8a.nu page while I was looking around for obscure boulder problems...clever name...sounds fun man!

name: Proud Mary
description: This extremely overhung line follows incut crimpers to the top of the boulder. Starting on two small jugs, either explode up and right to a small but positive crimp or reach your left hand to a bad slopey edge and lock off to the incut crimp. From here, get your left foot very high, and get left hand to a small gaston far away, using the incut intermediate next to it or just going straight to it. Grab a couple good holds and do a simple top out. As far as I know, this is the second hardest problem at the Beach. A lower start on two bad crimps may be possible when the sand is low... So iLL strong men, get out there!

name: Sex on the Beach
description: Starting on the good start holds of Jimbo's, head right on good crimps and jugs. Hit a huge jug in the middle of the face and go straight up to two incut crimpers. From here, move your left hand once more into a good, slightly slopey jug, hike your feet up and do a hard move to the final hold. Ultra classic. One of the only problems in the v6 range in So iLL on jugs!

name: Wash Out
description: Start on horizontal slopey crimps, pull the first move to a good side pull. The first move is the crux, and the problem is pretty much done after that. Holds will probably be sandy, so be careful!

name: [Redacted]
description: The top out of Dream Weaver/Driftwood. Start on good holds and top out.

name: Dream Weaver
description: This is a very strange/unique problem. Dream Weaver starts inside the cave, with left hand on a positive crimp undercling under the bulge, right on on a small edge side pull. Start the problem off with a tough first move, then find some way to work your way out the cave.

name: Driftwood
description: Start on low slopers and traverse right towards Dream Weaver. Driftwood has the same topout as Dream Weaver.

name: Huckleberry Finn
description: Start right around the arÃªte when coming into the cave, then climbing directly up, using pockets and slopey edges.

name: Booger Eater
description: Climb up the face to the left of King of Smears.

name: King of Smears
description: Climb through the vaguely featured face to nice holds on top. Classic V3

name: 2 Six-Packs, 1/5 of Scotch & A Full Moon
description: Begin with some high bouldering up a 5.5ish looking slab. Reach a 6ish foot protruding boulder with a flat top. Climb on top of that, Climb through 4 bolts to reach the top.

name: Africa
description: A fun toprope.

name: Cave City
description: Deep dihedral crack. fairly straightforward climbing. a fall while leading could be bad. several spots you'll have to squeeze through.

name: Detention
description: A few starting moves will get you to a large ledge, where you can place gear in the crack. Edges and jugs through bolts. Clipping stances are usually pretty good. Finish straight to the final horns; the chains are on the wall above the finish.

name: Dizzy
description: Pitch 1: Start on Unfinished Symphony but climb up and leftward towards the path of fixed gear. After the first clip climb up and leftward to anchor chains.    Pitch 2: Climb above the belay and continue through the gully to a safety bolt. Continue by angling up and right, then go around the exposede arete and up to the anchor. (most common route for pitch 2)    Pitch 2 Variation: "5.12a" From the belay, traverse rightward to the first bolt. From there crank through the roof and follow the arete to the anchor.

name: Fear of Flying
description: big long offwidth crack, that gets bulgy and dirty near the top. some real nice sit down rests near the top. finishes out with some face climbing. took me a while to figure out offwidth moves, but it was fun figuring it out. might want to wear pants and tape ankles or wear high top shoes (i've lost some skin to this one). i've only top roped this route using several trees at the top for anchors.

name: High Flying Bird
description: Climb the face, clipping the two bolts as you move working into the crack. Work you way through the crack as it widens and becomes slightly overhung. Climb over the ledge and reach the bolted anchor.

name: Let's Play Doctor
description: Thin and strenuous, bouldery start. Fun

name: Mike's Meander
description: A nice first trad climb. good stances for placing gear and good gear.

name: Seams Hard
description: Its the sport route that climbs a thin seam

name: Unfinished Symphony
description: Pitch 1-5.8 Starts about 30 feet left of the big off width. Start in the left facing dihedral with a thin crack. Follow crack system up and to the right. Go around corner and rig a hanging belay here. Pitch 2-5.10a ascend the ramp dihedral to a safety bolt and top out above.

name: Unknown Name
description: Begin on High Flying Bird and pull over the first bulge. From here work up and right, skipping the open book feature of H.F.B. and a word towards a bolt in a "honey comb" featured spot. Clip this bolt and pull the last strenuous bulge to reach the anchor.

name: No Name
description: Climb the vertical crack on the left side of the steep overhang.

name: Number 35
description: Begin by climbing up the short face, clipping two bolts as you go, and eventually reach the top

name: Moving Right Along
description: From the belay ledge, traverse leftward 15 feet and go up to the bolt located at the base of a gully. Climb the left side of the gully and go straight over the bulge to the top.     Variation (5.7) Stay with the crack at the top of the 2nd pitch.

name: Pioneers and Connoisseurs
description: Pitch: 1 (5.11) From the belay ledge, traverse rightward around the corner to the first bolt. An interesting upward reach move takes you to the second bolt. Continue about 25ft rightward across a ledge system to a fixed, hanging belay.    Pitch: 2 (5.7) Mantle above the belay and look up and right for the last bolt. Angle up and left to the top.

name: Sampson
description: Begin from the belay ledge, and go straight up. Move through the center of a gully and clip the bolt near the ledge. A long, easy slab tops it out.

name: "Thomas Bear Memorial"
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: April Fool
description: Climb the leftward angling dihedral feature

name: Big Sting
description: If necessary, use the oak tree to access the slab. Climb the slab to the right facing dihedral crack inside of the overhang. Once in, climb with the feature and top out on the left.     Jeff stirred the wasps, John made them mad, Brian got nailed!

name: Community Property
description: Climb the crack system "gully" protecting when necessary and eventually top the bluff out.

name: Cool Down
description: Enjoyable slab route. Starts with a crack in the middle. When that ends, you work your way left a tiny bit to a crack on that side.

name: Dos Equis
description: Head right look for the two X-like features in the rock about 15 feet up. A waist-high roof is underneath. Goes straight up.

name: Easter Beaver
description: Follow the bolts to reach the anchor

name: Ghosts and Goblins
description: Climb the large rounded arete with a psychological crux at 2/3 height

name: Hypothermia
description: Pitch 1: (5.8) Climb up the gully until you reach the base of the arete. Build a belay here.    Pitch 2: (5.10a) Traverse the dihedral crack (don't forget to clip the bolt) up and left to the next gully and belay at the tree.    Descent: 4th class out from here, or rappel from the tree

name: Jack In The Green
description: Ascend the slab/face next to a tree 12ish feet left of the actual bolt line. Traverse into the route and make careful moves until you traverse under an overhung arete. Ascend the upper arete and eventually reach the anchor.

name: The Lats Waltz
description: Ascend the shallow, easy looking gully above a low roof.     "Go Ahead, Make 'Em Dance"-E. Ulner

name: No Equis
description: Route on bulge just left of Dos Equis.  A bouldery start leads to relaxed climbing with not exactly ideal gear placements; get creative with mid size cams and nuts.  Joins with Dos Equis last two bolts to the anchors.

name: Regional Coordination
description: Ascend the right leaning seam that goes up a slab and continue with it as it becomes vertical, followed by going through a small open book gully. Continue until you reach a small ledge before you reach the top.

name: Schoolyard Blues
description: Fun face climb with a wild roof!

name: Schoolyard Squeeze
description: Climb the chimney crack to the left of Schoolyard Blues

name: St. Louis Graffiti
description: Short, fun and slightly fingery route near the end of the bluff

name: Vogue
description: Climb the face while following the bolt line.

name: Bouldering Cave
description: This is a nice little cave with the roof ranging in height from 4-12 feet.  Always stays dry and there are a handful of eliminates/problems possible - enough for a session or two.

name: Compression Ratio
description: Sidepulls galore. Beta I attempted: start sitting on sidepull edges/pinches, throwing high to more sidepull edges (good LH, semi-slopey RH) before moving to better holds above. Name totally made up (not in the guidebook, though I thought it worthy of description).

name: Pinch Point
description: Name totally made up (certainly not a FA but not in the guidebook, though I thought it worthy of description). Grade is a tired 4th-day-on estimate, so probably soft. From ledge at back of cave, slap to pinch on lip of the low roof tier. Use foot trickery of choice to bring LH to flat sidepull. Slap RH to another pinch, then move up on good ledges.

name: Pocket Thesaurus
description: Name totally made up (certainly not a FA but not in the guidebook, though I thought it worthy of description). Grade is a tired 4th-day-on estimate, so probably soft. From good ledges at the back of the cave, move straight out the cave to a close pair of positive ledges. From here, go to a slopey 2 finger LH pocket/pinch, then make a big RH move to a solid 4-finger pocketed ledge, probably cutting feet. Make another big move with the LH to a similarly positive pocket and begin the romp to the top on giant incut pockets.

name: Walkin' Spanish
description: From a sit at the starting edge, move through slopers, pinches, and an undercling to reach a pair of incut edges above. From there, move out left to a similar, smaller, pair of edges. Figure out the moves straight up to the big mouth-shaped ledge above, then top out through easier roof climbing above.

name: Hueco Problem
description: SDS just right of unnamed v3. Pinch, move to sidepull in big hueco and top out left in slopers or right in small, left-facing pockets.

name: Pink Maynjo
description: Sart on same jugs as the v4. Go left & reach around to the other face to match on sloping but positive edge. Top out Left.

name: Unnamed
description: 1st problem on overhung face. Jugs to start, left hand to fat slopey pinch, and top out the bulge.

name: Baptist
description: Facing "the son" directly to your left against the corner are the under cling starting holds. hit the huge block jug and up and right to the pad and a half flake, big stretch right again to a good hold then mantle the son.

name: Holy Ghost
description: Start on the two jugs next to "The Son" start, throw up to the pinch then to the jug on the lip, hit the high sloper and reach for the slopy rail with the seam in it, fire for the side pull Jug and finish the mantel.

name: The Son
description: Start matched low on the right side of the arete, throw around and out left to the bumpy rail, out high right to crimp seam and match, then shoot for the flat jug at the top, mantel.

name: Buck Mellow
description: Start with sidepull and undercling. Crux is getting to the upper banister crack. Feet are tricky.  A surprisingly good climb for what it is.Â

name: It Gets Easier
description: An old chimney on the side of a school, built out of stone rough enough to climb.

name: Unnamed
description: Not quite as high as the West Side Bridges but more technical.

name: Unnamed Left
description: Besides Glazed Doughnut, this is one of the hardest bridge routes. The mortar lines are really shallow and forces you to grab the features of the stone.     Beta. Shark tooth in the middle. Trails to the left.

name: Chalk Dust
description: Don't let the mortar cracks fool you.    There's a good grove for crimping every 2 stone layers. Not every stone layer.   This bridge support has been sprayed with a glaze coating to help prevent weathering. This is bad because it makes some spots smooth, this is also good because the route might be to easy without it.   Named after Kevin fell from the arc onto his chalk bucket that contained loose chalk. His face was powdery.

name: Coconut
description: The moves on this problem are not as repetitive as chalk dust.     Named after Kevin falling onto his unopened coconut water, causing it to spray and soak the pad.

name: Right Face
description: Start 4' to the right of the plastered crack.   Climb upward until you're roughly bridge level then start going right.

name: slippy
description: reference pictures for route. A fall could be bad since the ground is slanted and goes into the water. The wall takes over a week to dry after a rain and even then its still fairly wet.

name: I Want My Money Back
description: Sit start on the vertical arete of the tall boulder and make literally one move before mantling

name: Jill's Special
description: Work your way up about two moves before mantling on the flat part of the boulder

name: Just A Dollar
description: Sit start with the first move as the crux. Make an awkward throw to a ledge and work your way up from there.

name: Sear's Tower
description: Crouch start on the two deep crimps with a right flag. The first move is the crux: left hand to another deep crimp above. Then, right foot step right arm up, and catch the top with your left hand.

name: Wicker Man
description: Start on the right side of the boulder, without using the lip traverse left around the arete and top out on the overhanging far side

name: Traverse to clown town
description: The pictures show where the hands are. The feet are open, but that being said the rock is so crumbly that solid foot holds are spread out a little bit.

name: Under the fallen tree
description: The middle has some sharp crimpy holds. Some of the holds nearby are loose so double check what you are grabbing.

name: Pockets Full of Sunshine
description: The small pockets on this wall are the perfect size for your middle and index fingers. Climb the pockets to the top out.  Video of First Ascent

name: Pillers
description: Top out on the piller then thereâs and easy down climb to the top of the wall then down climb the wall.Â

name: Dabalicious
description: The crux is attempting not to dab. I had to use a lot of heel hooks to accomplish this. The route would be pretty nice if the dirt mounds weren't in the cave. It is a scrunched up route with some awkward moves. Any and all rock inside the cave is on. Route starts further back in the cave, and then follows the same line as The Great Escape. Traverse the side of the cave to the left and out, the rails toward the back of the cave seem to be constantly moist so chalk is nice.    If you are climbing this route, you must be desperate for a climb!

name: The Great Escape
description: Work your way out through the entrance of the cave, mantle and finish on top of the rock. There are at least three jugs, and a majority of the route is a large rail. Any and all rock inside the cave is on. Don't use the rail marked in the main page's photo, it's chossy and let's not break it. There is a pretty solid heel hook near the end of the route, kind of fun.

name: Pandemic
description: Traverse the front of the cave. Start by sliding down into the left hand opening as far as you can, then go up and right, finishing by mantling onto the rock pedestal on the climbers right of the right entrance.  Avoid the rail marked on the main photo (use the lip of the cave above it), its pretty hollow sounding!

name: Firelight
description: See picture for what's on. End is anticlimactic.

name: Holy Ground
description: See picture for what's on. Along the bottom of the wall, the concavity and the rail just below it (a few mm wide) are also on. Crux is the start.

name: In Vain
description: See picture for what's on. Small hands match more easily.

name: Mad World
description: See picture for what's on. Along the bottom of the wall, the concavity and the rail just below it (a few mm wide) are also on for different beta.

name: Mercy Mirror
description: See picture for what's on. Do whatever to get to the start.

name: Trophy Hunter
description: See picture for what's on. For the starred holds, try to avoid using the tops. Crux is at the end. Can also be done in reverse.

name: Use Your Words
description: Use the words on the school sign to get to the top.

name: Nutri Grain
description: This boulder is made of concrete conglomerate rock that lays on an old railway structure. It tops out at over 15 ft and is a slab-style boulder until the very end. The name "Nutri Grain comes from the very crumbly concrete rock that makes up the boulder. This one will take some problem solving and make sure to be careful, the rock isn't all that strong so don't beat on it.Â The Crux comes just before the top out; look for a small indent in the rock for your right foothold then get a side pull on the arete to bring your left foot up just before you top out.Crash Pads and Spotters HIGHLY recommended! This boulders top out is pretty high and there is a risk of serious injury with and especially without spotters and pads.Â

name: Always All Ways
description: This is a "Figure 8" traverse. Start off matching both hands on the north west point of the rock at the blue mark with feet on the green marks. Traverse right using the crack at the red line mark and various holds below it. Do not use a hold above the red line. Work your way under the middle cave and out to the south east face of the rock, avoiding any hold above the red line. Work around the south face and traverse left along the south west face to the cave again, following the same guidelines. Route is complete when hands and feet make it to the north starting point.

name: Blue Line
description: Follow the obvious line to the top

name: Cold Pockets
description: Pockets only

name: Criss Cross Applesauce Dyno
description: Dyno to the top from the start holds

name: Days of Our Quarantine Lives
description: On the same boulder as Rock-a-bye Baby  Stand start using only top ring and bottom ring of the Boulder. Start jugs on right and traverse the whole and end at start holds.Â   Good warm up boulder.Â

name: Hot Pockets
description: West face of "Big boulder." Sit start, climb pockets only, all other holds are barred!

name: Reverse Ring Around The Toesies
description: Start on the opposite side of Ring Around the Toesies and top out at the start of Ring Around the Toesies.Â

name: Ring Around the Toesies
description: Hands start on the West face, toe hook the ledge on the East face. Work your way underneath the arch to the East side of the boulder. Do NOT use any section of the boulder below the circled areas in the photos.

name: Rock-A-Bye-Baby
description: Heel hook around the boulder then rock up on your heel to top out. Hands start on SW face of the boulder. Do NOT use any section of the boulder below the hand start.

name: Switch Up
description: Sit start with hands on the bottom two blue marks and feet on the green marks. Press up to grab the small crack circled blue. Your feet can only touch the two original footholds and the two starting handholds. Dyno to the top, directly in the middle, grabbing hold of a small slab that sits about 8 inches in from the edge. Do not grab the edge of the top rock! After grabbing, your feet can go anywhere to top out.

name: What in Tar-nation
description: Start on a left hand crimp and a right hand sloper with a heel down and to the left. right hand throw to a slopey crimp rock up on your left heel and throw left hand to a small sloper rail. Then right hand bump to a sharp crimp. stand on your left foot and move your left hand to the final sloper. Easy top out.

name: Baby Yoda
description: Start on the sloping ledge with your body as low as possible. Use the pocket feet and throw to the top sloper, then work your way to the top out. The holds the the left are off, and the sign is off. Only use the sloping ledge, the top, and the pocket feet.Â

name: The Dark Side
description: Â Basically the goal is to move up left from the start. You have to find your way around and over the bulge. That is the crux of the problem. Start with a left hand on the sloping ledge, and right hand on the low crimp. Sit start again, may be a little less of a sit if you are shorter.  This one is a bit more contrived. Only use the low right foot for a bomber heel. Then don't use that ledge after. Also, only use the right hand hold to begin the boulder, it is off for a foot. I've x'd out the areas on the photo. Harder if you are short.

name: The Force Awakens
description: Start on the low left incut. This is where your left hand and left heel goes. Then you have a high right hand on the sloper, you have a small buldge where you can catch the sloper more securely. Pulling up into the start is the first hard part. Then match the sloper, shift the hands, find a better left heel, then big drive up into The Dark Side finish.   Just don't use The Dark Side's starting crimp for any reason, or right most juggy crimp. Anything below the waist foot wise is on. The photo's have more info.   Bring out your inner Jedi!

name: Ketamine
description: Start on a tiny right hand crimp and a sharp and small crystal for the left. Put your foot in any of the pockets below. Establish off of the ground then fire to the lip.Â

name: The Light Side
description: Start the same as The Dark Side but then go to the left while staying on the good foot. Make some crossing slaps then pull yourself around the bulge. Climb the slab to top out.Â

name: Meditation
description: Sit start at the obvious left crimp and right sidepull crimp as seen on the photo's. Follow the line directly up and through the face. Throw a high right heel to make your way up, but no standing on that same right ledge to help you top out. You gotta climb that slab!

name: Abundance of Caution
description: Traverse of SE wall starting low and working uphill/east using the limestone holds. Sandstone top cap is off (except for easternmost pillar).

name: Corner of Happy and Healthy
description: Climb up the corner of the SE face of the bridge. Only the sandstone cornerstones are on. it may be possible to do without using the short line of cornerstones under the mantle but I couldn't work it out right now.

name: Crack Pipe
description: Only use the sandstone cornerstones on the vertical arete and top out on the mantle. The crack is off, and the pipe/conduit is off. Once sent, either climb onto the bridge deck and walk back down or downclimb using the limestone holds to your right.

name: Lady(bug) Killer
description: Straight up the main column of the SE face of the bridge. Only the limestone is on.

name: Steelworkers Crack
description: Chicago Park District may not have planned for this to be part of the climbing at Steelworkers Park, but it is too obvious and appealing to be ignored. Â Surprisingly nice, if short, you climb up the fingers crack to the top of the ore wall, where you can enjoy a nice view downtown and to the active steel works in Indiana. Most of the route you can cheat the crack a bit with bonus features on the sides, especially the two boreholes, but towards the top you are committed into the crack for a couple moves. Â Bits of iron sticking out give an easy topout up and left, but don't forget to place a final directional cam or clip the I-beam if you are anchoring off the main barrel. Â You can climb up the regular wall and set a TR in the same way. The bits of gravel at the very edge of the crack have the potential to pop, but mostly feels fine, and you can place gear solidly into it.

name: Tar and Feathered
description: Sit start on right hand crimp rail and left hand sloper. Climb up and right using various slopers and crimps and make a committing move to a final jug. Watch out for dabs on this lowball!

name: Turret (Tar-arete)
description: Sit start with left hand side pull crimp and right hand low on the arete. Hard to get off the ground. Bump up the right hand and make your way straight up. All of the arete is good. I tried to avoid using any of the holds from "tar and feathered".Â

name: Tell 'em you're with Mac
description: Tell 'em you're with Mac is a 255 ft (77.7 m) section of wall (within the Pacific Union Traverse crag) that runs along Kinzie Avenue between cross streets Hart Ave. and Wolcott Ave. This route was broken down into thirteen 20â sectors, based off of the metal poles that line the Pacific Union rail at the top of the wall. The distance between any two markers is approximately 10 ft. Start at the metal gate on Hart St and traverse east to the Wolcott Ave. There are two major boulder problems as cruxes. However, the real challenge is linking 255 feet of crimps, slopers, gastons, underclings, side pulls, and small footholds without getting pumped. Finding a midway no-hands rest just before the first major crux (140 ft mark) is key to sending this beast of a route.Entry from the first ascent on July 29, 2020: "Two years, 255 ft of wall. I cleaned every hold along the 255 ft stretch with a toothbrush. I went through 3 toothbrushes. Since 2018 I cleared a total of 765 feet of weeds from the base of the wall with my machete and bare hands. I mapped 13 individual 20 ft sectors by tape measure and camera, putting pictures of each sector in a ppt file. I worked separately on each section developing and memorizing hundreds of individual sequences. I separated my shoulder twice and was blinded from debris and ended up in a clinic once. The wall drew blood on three occasions. Today at 6 PM I sent my project and traversed all 255 ft in one try."Â

name: Spiderjam
description: A beautiful, one of a kind continuous roof crack hidden like a true gem amidst the beauty of Cedar Lakes western shore.Â  No, really, it's worth it. Starts with greatÂ Fists/Hands for several moves before a challenging final not-quite-fingers-not-quite-Hands-battle before exiting the cave to a hang and drop. Two to three pads are enough.  Bring a towel if itâs seeping it can be dried out in a day. Â If you see it dry, donât hesitate.  Oh, and bring a spider stick

name: left face
description: Climb the tricky water runnel up to a roof.  Do some creative stemming to pull the roof and reach the anchors.

name: Middle Face
description: Several bolts of pumpy pocket climbing leads to a mediocre rest.  The crux is moving past the final bolt to the anchors and is difficult to read.

name: Right Face
description: This is an enjoyable climb that ascends the right side of the dugout.  It is comparable in difficulty to the Middle Face.  However, the anchors are inexplicably located about ten feet past the logical end of the route, requiring the use of a rusty upward driven bolt to aid to the anchors.  The sandy boulder problem this bolt protects is probably possible (grade is an estimate), but not nearly as quality as the rest of the route.  A lower set of anchors would decrease the grade to about 11D and increase the overall quality.

name: Tongue & Groove
description: Work along the left side of the grooved arete using a variety of holds on solid stone. Â A fun climb that's more challenging than it appears from the ground. Â If reach is an issue for certain sections, climbing towards the gully will yield a way around.

name: Unkown Crack
description: 5.9 climbing to crux move at the roof when traversing right to the anchors on Middle Face. Very exposed move, and has potential for pendulum swing into opposite wall. Not sure if anyone has climbed this route before. When traversing I knocked off a large rock that almost hit my belayer.

name: Back Room
description: This is the dihedral chimney on the right side of the amphitheater.    I know almost nothing about this route.  The name was provided by Jim.  The grade is a complete guess, only included because a grade is required to submit the route to the site.

name: Dune
description: Slightly longer and more difficult than inception.  Follow inception until you get on top of the worm-like sloping feature with a crack running along the bottom.  Rather than clipping the sixth bolt on inception, clip a bolt to your right, and traverse this feature to the right for about 15 feet and head up out the roof. Three cruxes of increasing difficulty separated by mediocre rests will take you to the anchors.    As with Inception, it is HIGHLY recommended that you clean the first five or six draws on TR to avoid a dangerous swing.  It is easiest if you clean the anchors and all of the draws that you can reach easily while lowering, then toprope it to get the first ones.  Alternately, on the last go of the day, you can leap frog the draws on the traverse, cleaning as you go, then get the rest on lower.

name: Generation Gap
description: The route is split in half by a no hands ledge in the dihedral.  The bottom and top are of comparable difficulty, but with very different styles.  After the initial boulder problem, head straight up until the third bolt.  The route initially went straight up to a series of sloping horizontals above the bolt and then left.  Since then, a critical crimp has been considerably downsized.  It is probably easier now to do the bouldery traverse below the bolt, join the dihedral and climb up to the bolt.      After the rest ledge, head left and enjoy quality overhanging slopers to the anchors.  Be sure to give a soft catch for the upper crux, as you tend to swing into the slab below.

name: Heingerous
description: This route follows a crack system just left of the chimney on the right side of the amphitheater.  Climb the layback crack and plug some gear at the top of it to protect the bouldery moves to the first bolt.  Crank through the steep crux, place some gear, and relax once you can stem on the wall behind you.  The face above is bolted and moderate, but a little scary due to the amount of dirt and lichen, as well as the ledge below.      Rebolted May 2012.

name: Inception
description: Extremely fun.  Head right after pulling the low roof and follow the ledge for several bolts.  Get a good rest before embarking on the quality overhang above.  Stay on your toes for several bolts of slopey, bouldery climbing.      Difficult to get back on after taking the huge whipper at the end of the crux.  A tighter catch helps there.

name: Legacy
description: Begin low and left in the amphitheater, work up and right through the first two bolts. Above the third bolt is the first bolt of legacy. From here follow the bolts through a series of side pulls, slopers, and edges to reach the final section. A technical slab wait for you at the top. Get psyched!

name: Slimy Arches
description: This is the large arching crack on the left side of the main amphitheater wall.  Large to medium sized gear will protect most of the route.  You can lower off of the sport route that meets the crack to avoid the somewhat chossy finish.  To get your money's worth, you can lower off of the anchors for Inception.

name: Lunar Landing
description: Follows the arete right of the roof crack.  Any additional info on the route would be appreciated.

name: Ralphie's Ruse
description: Follow crimps past the first few bolts and easier climbing to the anchors.   Variation:  Climb the tricky pockets ten feet right of the start, clipping three bolts, and join Ralphie's at the fourth bolt. makes for a better warm-up once you figure out the sequence.  FA: Phillip Carrier 2011

name: Ralphie's Variation
description: The easier variation of Ralphie's Ruse. Fun pocket pulling ties your back into the main route.

name: Red Ryder
description: This line is deceptively slopey and difficult.  The crux in the middle of the route is very cool but hard to read.  Pumpy.

name: Roof Crack
description: Information on this route was from Jim, who has not climbed the route in a long time.  It follows a short roof crack on the prominent arete of Moon Rock.

name: Phillip's Overhang
description: After a few bolts of surprisingly tricky climbing on big holds, head right out the overhang and up into the large water groove.

name: Shout
description: Climb the prominent arete, which is sandy and tricky, up to a sandy ledge below a roof.  Do some big moves to gain jugs at the lip and make the clip.  A difficult boulder problem on tiny crimps and pockets gets you to the anchors.

name: Rivers of Avalon
description: Start with some small crimps, small feet and a tiny sidepull/pocket thing and go up to bigger, better holds and an easy topout.

name: Auld Lang Syne
description: The problem starts at the bottom right of the cave climbs to meet the other wall, then goes up to a slab top out filled with lots of moss and moisture.

name: And a Happy New Year
description: This problem is on the front left corner of the boulder if you are facing the creek, sit start off a sloper to a small crimp, then move the left hand to another crimp then the right hand to the top, short problem, but fun to work out.

name: The Persian Wall
description: In the middle of the wall you will see a V-shaped notch beneath an overhang resting on a smooth undercut bed of rock. this is the Persian Wall. Climb, if you can, straight up the wall, through the notch, and over the overhang at it's widest part 45' to the top.

name: Standard
description: Climb straight up over a couple of overhangs.     This is the route I did back in 1965. It wasn't V4-John Gill

name: Rebuttal
description: According to Sandstone Warrior, "rumored to be John Gill's hardest problem".

name: Retable
description: Start on decent edges, climb up and out through a slopey top out

name: Sit Start V1
description: Sit start and pull through good holds to a slopey topout

name: V4 Face
description: Harder then the problem to the left, great slopey top out

name: Corner
description: Start low on an pocket you can undercling. Pull the difficult mantel

name: Dwarf
description: Sit start from a jug and move up and right. Push hard through a mantle and finish. Short and sweet.

name: Miller High Life
description: Sit start down low, work your way out and up on obviously rails and jugs till you reach a set up slopers and top out. Protection: Pads and Spotters

name: One Move Wonder
description: Begin in cave feature. pull hard and reach to a lip, top out from there.Â

name: Road Worthy
description: Sit start low on the left corner and finish and top out on Roadside Wall

name: Roadside Wall
description: Many fun variations on this wall leading up to the top out of "Miller High Life"

name: Ships Prow
description: Begin as low as you can. Pul through good holds to some large throws out right, pull the slopey top out.Â

name: Warm up Boulder
description: Climb up and down the obvious Iron flakes. Top out is doable, but needs to be cleaned up.Â

name: Gill Traverse
description: Begin in the crack,traverse to the right and then head up. Fun problem

name: Arete
description: great warm up one hard gastone move

name: Classic Face
description: Climb the different options

name: K Problem
description: Climb up the boulder to a great pinch

name: Pocket Slab
description: Slabby start, to good pockets towards the top of the boulder. Find feet and stand up reaching for pockets and top out.Â

name: V3 Arete
description: Start a low as you can with your left hand on the arete and your right hand on a undercling

name: Undercling Problem
description: Begin on the undercling and have fun figuring out how to top out!

name: the matrix
description: start standing on awkward chest-height holds. throw for top.

name: storm and rain
description: starts under small roof with right hand on big sloper, left on edge under roof. move up, over roof, and towards arete/top

name: Fancy Lads
description: This is a high quality line with great movement on solid rock.    P1 (5.10c):  Follow bolt line to a roof with anchors.  This is a great pitch by itself and many people only do this pitch.    P2 (5.11d or 5.9 C1) Pull the roof on crimps and sidepulls to good incut flakes protected by bolts.  The step slightly right into a Flared crack with good jams in the back of it.  Exit the crack left at the top on good edges.

name: Genuine Risk
description: This climbs the left of the twin cracks under a roof with a perfect handsized slot.  Pull the roof using the slot and pull into a left facing dihedral.  At the top traverse right and take the path of least resistance.  Use caution on the traverse (5.9) as a fall here could get ugly quick.  This is probably why it is named Genuine Risk.  The 11 crux is very well protected by mid-sized cams

name: High Over Camp
description: This climbs the V chimney/dihedral to a roof.  The roof is a hand/fist crack that is set deep in a flared chimney of sorts; but, the jams are solid.  Pull through on jams into an easy 5.7ish chimney that leads to a two bolt chain anchor.

name: Kittens
description: The Crux is between 2nd - 3rd bolt and another b/t 4 and 5.  The route is very sustained so pace yourself.  The second pitch is a bit scary getting to the first bolt.  You will hit a ledge if you blow the move.

name: Trial and Error
description: This is a seldom done trad line at Draper's, but it is fantastic.  The crux short 15'..but burly.  The top is a little scary and one move is protected by a manky rusted piton.

name: The Outline
description: This route is fantastic!  Esp. if you do it as one long pitch!    P1:  The crux is getting to the first bolt.  Bouldery and technical.  Then things ease up.    P2:  Crux is the b/t 1st and 2nd bolt.  A bit difficult clipping 2nd bolt may want to commit past the clip to the jug...then clip it.

name: Sidewinder
description: Take a right when main trail runs into wall,about 75 feet up small hill right before left facing dihedral.

name: Southern Exposure
description: P1: Follow a broken crack system to a 2 tier roof to a sustained traverse into an alcove dihedral.    P2: Airy but easy traverse to a spactacular and bolt protected face.

name: Ant Killer
description: Fantastic 5.9 Dihedral Crack.  P2 not as classic.

name: Bloody Nose
description: P1  Chimney up to a slab.   P2 Airy and fun travers to a perch.  Continue to traverse left around the arete.

name: C-Crack
description: Go up the easy crack system until you hit a roof.  Either continue up the roof for the direct variation, or as I recomend, head right on the horizontal, near footless, hand crack traverse.  Finish on the antkiller belay ledge.

name: C-Crack Direct
description: Start as C-Crack, the at the traverse rip up the overhanging hand crack.

name: D & D's Pecker Wrecker
description: Fingery route down low with a triangular roof (that one can cop a nice sit down rest on) halfway up.  Difficulties ease once you surmount the roof.

name: Geppetto
description: 5.8 climbing that is separated by a crux off of two somewhat thin crimps through a slight bulge (this can be dynoed through though if you wish for a more fun variation)

name: Shorty
description: Located in a pile of boulders before the 45 degree wall, and behind two trees. Sit start with left hand on crimp, and right in pocket. Send from there.

name: Bass Assassin
description: Start with left hand on side pull, right on slopy edge. fire to the crimp, then shoot for the jug.

name: Desperado
description: Sit start with matched hands on a big sloppy pinch pocket. Throw out to a pinch on the arete. Pull yourself around the arete. The problem ends when you stand up on the face to the left of the arete. Good problem.

name: Smitty's House
description: Begin with your hands matched on small edges. Once set, throw out big to the right for a blocky pinch. Top out from there.

name: Touch of Nature
description: From crimps at face level, move out to the cool slopey pinch feature, then continue out right on seam crimps to the obvious incut pocket, then up to the finish rail. Hang & drop.

name: Goreville Youth
description: Begin on the lowest jug. Classic Southern Illinois sloppy topout.

name: First Born
description: Start at the base of the overhung, rightward angling arete. Go straight up the face, staying out of the dihedral.     Note: If desiring to lead First Born a rehearsal is recommended. The dihedral offers the only protection for gear. First Born in recent times is usually top roped

name: First Climb (aka Psychopath)
description: A fun romp up a groove with a crack in the bottom.    Solid rock.  Easy cruisin'.

name: Hawk's Beak
description: Work up right facing dihedral around to right-face, up through split in rock to large sloping ledge. move into large water groove/chimney for about 10 ft of crux climbing to slight overhang and "cedar" tree   at top.

name: Missouri Breaks
description: Begin by climbing through a small overhang on good holds. Continue through the continuous crack that angles to the right.

name: Open Book (aka I Don't Care)
description: Climb the well protectable dihedral.

name: Under The Influence
description: Climb the dihedral crack, crux is midway up.

name: Anchors Away AKA Enchained Melody
description: This route traverses almost the entire length of the cliff. From the anchors of "Drunkards Crack" all the way across the bluff to the anchors of "Easy Crack". The climbing isn't that difficult, there are some tricky down climbing sections as well as a couple of run out spots. It's a fun way to get some easy mileage in and to touch some holds you probably haven't touched before. I belayed the second at the anchors for GrÃ¡ves and the anchors for The Chimney.

name: Barnes Overhang
description: Work your way up the slab and through pocketed holds in the overhang.

name: The Bulge
description: Start on the short rightward tieback. Pull the mantel shelf about 10 feet up. Then go straight up to the top while staying 6 feet left of George's chimney.

name: Camel's Hump
description: This popular TR goes up the huge hump in the wall. By placing a picnic table at the base of the climb, you can make the start easier. Begin at the bottom-right of the hump and climb up toward the center. Top out through vertical bucket climbing. According to the 1972 guide Sandstone Climber, "every inch of the Camels Hump has been climbed."

name: Charlieâs Traverse
description: Start up Crackpot until you get to third bolt then cut left all the way to City Limits. You will pass through the cave on Graves on the way. Keep traversing until you reach the rest after City Limits crux. Finish the upper wall on City Limits. Long draw on the third bolt of crackpot eliminates any rope drag.

name: Chimney
description: Start at the bottom left, follow the crack up to the chimney, pull through the chimney.

name: City Limits
description: One of the first 5.12's in the country. Starting on good holds, climb the overhanging pocketed face. Rest on the slab about midway up, then pull your way up the next overhang. The pocket pulling was futuristic for its time.    The initial crux has been soloed by Adam Grosowsky, Alan Carrier, and Jim Thurmond. Also has been led by Jim Thurmond through the upper section overhang in the late 1980's

name: Crackpot
description: Climb the overhanging crack system into the little cave straight above, continue above it and top out.

name: Dead Dog
description: Layback the crack that comes out of the right side of the cave feature. Follow the first crack system until a horizontal, iron-banded ledge, clip the bolt and traverse right into the other crack system. Follow the crack and place gear as you climb. NOTE! As you near the end of the crack, excellent horizontal gear placements emerge. Pull the face moved under the upper bulge of the climb and clip a bolt. Face moves up and right lead to the anchor.  Note: this is an excellent route that leads very well with gear. Bolts are exactly where you need them.

name: Dead Dog Walking
description: Climb to the small cave feature then work through the overhung crack feature until it ends. Step up on a slabby face and work through face holds and pockets and eventually reach the anchor.Â

name: Diagonal Direct
description: Climb the sloping face and work your way to the anchor of Drunkard's Crack.

name: Dim View
description: PLEASE NOTE: If unfamiliar, it is recommended to stick clip the first bolt. Dim View is not as straight forward as it may seem. Also, due to the span between bolts 1 and 2, make sure your belayer is on their "A Game", to keep you off the ground if a fall were to occur.     Start on the small boulder in the ground for Return To Forever, from there climb up and left, when you reach the first big horizontal go straight up from there, eventually pulling through the jug chair, pick the path of least resistance to top out to Jill's anchor.

name: Double Barrel
description: After locating to two large pockets (the end of the double barrel), climb up following the straightest path. One of the more contiguous vertical routes on the bluff.    Note: gear placements are limited in the lower section, but improve as you continue higher. Not recommended without trad rehersal.

name: Drunkard's Crack
description: Its the obvious wide crack that leads to the top. Commonly soloed to set more difficult routes. Great route for teaching traditional placements.

name: Dumb View
description: Climb Dim View on trad gear. Boulder through crux sequence about 20 ft to good stance and some good but small gear( .75 and blue or purple Metolius TCU). Pull through the next pumpy sequence to reach another break which will take a #1 or #2 BD Cam.Â  Â Climb through the upper crux, sling the horn if you'd like then on to the anchors.

name: Easy Crack
description: Climb through the fractured crack system, eventually working you way through the pocketed upper face to the anchor.     Note: make sure you find the horizontal gear placement before leaving the wide upper crack.

name: Electric Kool-Aid Acid Test
description: Begin at the base of Makanda Layback and climb up and left of M.L. setting yourself to climb up through the blank face

name: Full Moon Foot Dance
description: This is the no-hands version of Drunkards Crack.

name: George's Direct
description: Start directly below on the right side and make you way towards the chimney, plug your way through the gully crack.

name: Georges Nose
description: Start on George's Direct but avoid the gully/crack system. Continue stright up, pulling directly throught the "nose" on the right side of the gully/crack. Follow path of least resistance.    Note: not recommended without trad rehersal.

name: Graves
description: PLEASE NOTE: If unfamiliar with the beginning sequence, it is highly recommended to stick clip the first bolt.     (Pronounced GROVZ) "not recommended to be led without rehearsal" With small cave located climb through pockets, face holds, and side pulls to eventually reach the infamous cave of Graves, from there traverse left until you reach the small gully above the main crack of Jill's, plug and chug your way to the "jug chair", clip the old safety piece and top out.

name: The Gully
description: Either choose to move a picnic table to the juggy ledge to aid in starting the route, or begin directly under the Camel's Hump and traverse left into the gully. Either way, stay left of Camel's Hump and work up through the slab towards jugs.

name: Hip Pocket
description: Beginning a few feet left of Joe's. Locate the large pinch hold and crank up the face. Use a series of side pulls, edges, and underclings to reach the bulge. Reach out right, stick the pocket and work your way over the bulge using pockets and a life saving edge. Easier moves to the anchor from here.

name: Hot Toddy
description: Beginning with a unique high stepping mantle, balance over on your feet using shallow divots. Layback, high step, and slab climb your way to the anchor.Â

name: The Idiot
description: Starting just to the right of the tree, climb up for about 20 feet. Then continue up and right for 30 more feet, crossing back onto Dead Dog.  Continue by climbing through iron bands and finish by Cedar tree.

name: Jill's
description: PLEASE NOTE: Jill's is difficult from the start. If you are not sure about the gear either stick clip or rappel down from the three eye bolts placed on top of the bluff and preplace you gear before attempting. This route is extremely fun, but unless you know the gear, you may be running serious risk.     Send the leftward leaning dihedral crack using pocketed holds on the left for feet "kinda hard to place gear", climb over the first bulge and look for gear placements, continue straight up looking for traditional placements, climb past the jug chair and reach the top for a good place to clip in.

name: Joe's Variation
description: Originally, you were to ascend the left facing crack system continuing straight above. Now, you begin just right of the original crack and climb the face.

name: Layback Hump Linkup
description: This climb is similar to Drunkards in the way of how it angles to the right and is well protected. This is a great climb for those learning trad. Crux is either the crux of Makanda Layback or getting off the ground for The Gully

name: Makanda Layback
description: Pull on small jugs to enter the gully crack, layback to the right and pull moves to eventually reach up left to nice horizontal edges, from there proceed to climb to the safety bolt "place a nut in the crack to the right to beef up the anchor point", then continue to the top through a rather blank section eventually meeting the last face, angle up and left eventually toping out and reaching the anchor. Fairly Committing Lead...

name: Monkey Moves
description: Climb over the small hump using a few ticks moves. Work up the apex of that feature and continue to the top.

name: My Feet Are Smiling
description: PLEASE NOTE: If unfamiliar with the route, it is recommended to stick clip the first bolt.     Beginning on Graves, head up and right to a 2 foot "peanut" shaped hueco. From there work left for about a move, then back right and up through a honeycomb section into the cave of Crackpot. Work out and up the face to the anchor.

name: Nowhere
description: Begin with the short, overhung start. Pull up and stand on iron-band ledge. Pull up and to the "pentagonal" hand pocket. Continue up the slab to a 3-finger pocket. Pull the move and follow good holds to the finish.

name: Open Book Direct
description: Begin at the base of the Makanda Layback, climb up and left to the bowling ball pocket, climb out through the Open Book gully.   Variation: Begin by climbing through the gully of Makanda Layback after climbing through its gully, traverse left into the open book formation and go up it.

name: Poison Ivy Center
description: Pull through the short moderate boulder problem to the base of the gully crack, mantle into the gully and enjoy.

name: Poison Ivy Right
description: Climb through the dihedral layback leftward to the base of the gully crack.

name: Rappellers' Demise
description: From the two stacked pockets climb through the upside down V formation and stay to the right of crackpot cave.

name: Right Side Route
description: High angle step climbing. Follow the water groove

name: Saluki Strut
description: Clip the bolt before pulling pulling the first bulge. Tricky is putting it mildly. Get your feet set, use the left hand side pull at the top of the seam almost directly below the first bolt. Reach up, grab the crimp with your right hand, and slap your way up the big sloper feature on the left. Climb the face and reach the bulge. Use a right handed, 2 finger pocket and perform a hard sidepull while getting your feet high to reach a decent left handed edge. Crank through and climb a short face to reach an anchor.Â

name: Shake and Bake
description: Climb the leftward angling crack system that juts off of the Chimney. Place cams until the angling flake feature meets the bolt line. Clip bolts from here to safely protect.Â

name: Shake And Bake Direct
description: Begin up the ramp that leads to the Chimney. Refer to photo for specifics. Climb up the face, trick side pulls, work into the large undercling feature, then out through pockets and face holds. Stay left of the Shake N Back crack system, and right of Geroges Nose.

name: Shotgun
description: Climb the layback crack system through the overhang. When the crack ends, continue on small pockets while following the straightest paths.    Note: Not recommended without trad rehersal.

name: Slightly Harder Crack
description: Climb up the slab to reach the wide gully at the base of the crack. Pull the tricky move and enjoy casual climbing to the anchor.

name: Smooth City
description: Staying to the right of Camel's Hump, climb the smooth face and skip the larger holds on the left.

name: Standing On Air
description: This is a short but sweet route. Standing On Air truly begins when the featured slab of Drunkard's Crack meets the wall just left of the small wash. Climb up the face using small nubblets.

name: Step Ladder
description: Another high angle staircase of a climb. Easy goes it. Good first lead.

name: Tempura Tour "Classic"
description: This is the grand traverse that lets one venture across the Shelter 1 Bluff line. This route allows you to climb high above the grassy field below and avoids the harder sections underneath the overhang. A must for anyone desiring to explore the vertical sphere of the bluff. Absolute Classic!

name: Tempura Tour "Complete"
description: Tempura Tour Complete is the full route that extends Tempura Tour from the belay chair above Jills, moves down Poison Ivy, and traverses the rest of the way towards George's.     This route offers some fun exposure and is well protected, especially at the cruxes. It is a true tour of Shelter 1.

name: Tiny Dancer
description: While performing a ballet of sorts, use some creative footwork to stem and smear your way up the wide gulley. Pull on good face holds to crank through the bulge and reach the top.Â

name: Walk Up
description: Start by laying back the flake. Continue up and pull through the weakness in the overhang and continue to a narrow "S" shaped stripe. Continue laying back and move up and right to top out.

name: Walking Gunslinger
description: Begin on Walk Up and make your way to the iron band jug at the first bolt. From here work right an up through a huge hueco to eventually reach the fourth bolt on Shotgun. Climb up to Shotgun's anchor to finish

name: 1,2,3 (aka The Rasp)
description: Climb through the triple overhanging system. Protects well on lead

name: Bittersweet
description: Climb the angling, featured ramping face until you reach a steep wall at the top. Find the key holds to make the clip. Call it good from there, or very burly moves lead you to the top out. (top out variation 5.12-?)

name: G.C. Blacktop
description: Beginning a few feet left of Scales of Iron, climb up using slopey edges eventually gaining access to unique iron banded holds. Follow the path of lease resistance to reach the top.Â

name: Gulley Cruiser
description: Follow the broken crack system to the top, place gear when necessary

name: Jacks Crack
description: Climb the crack on the left edge of the Gill Roof.

name: Merit Badge
description: Climb the featured slab, using an assortment of holds to reach the top

name: Name Unknown
description: Climb the crack left of Slip. Crux is low

name: Scales of Iron
description: Climb the face left of UnknownÂ

name: The Scout
description: Climb the clean extremely features slab.

name: Slip
description: From the foot trail, eye up the path of least resistance and go from there. The crux is in the lower section.

name: Virginia Creeper
description: Climb the featured face up the angling wall.Â

name: Vultures On Parade
description: Climb the bulging arete feature 6 feet left of 1,2,3.Â

name: A Fissure of Green
description: Climb up the crack system that divides the slabby face. Follow the crack, protecting as needed, until the crack ends. At the end of the crack, work up and left to a bolt, then stem your way out the top. Refer to photo for anchor location.Â

name: Canyoneer Slab Extension
description: Climb the Canyoneering Route or Fissure Of Green and upon reaching the anchors, continue climbing through two more bolts to an even higher 1/2 inch eyebolt anchor setup. A fun continuance of an already creative route.Â

name: Canyoneering Route
description: Begin up a featured slabby face utilizing creative moves. When it becomes more difficult, turn off your tunnel vision, and let yourself lean back

name: County Line Divide
description: Pitch 1: Beginning in Fissure of Green or the Canyoneering Route, climb up and build and anchor at the anchor behind the Super Slab Boulder.  Pitch 2: Walk right along the ledge and over to a bolted route that goes up an angled slab to the left of a roof formation.  Descent: A 60 meter rope can get you to the ground from the anchor of pitch 2. It will be easier to get to the ground by a pitch 2 rappel  Fun Note: This route lies almost directly on the border of Union and Jackson County.Â

name: Dining With The Devil
description: Make you way up some low angle boulders, and climb on top of a ledge. Pull on good holds that aren't easy to find and make your way to the top. A fun addition to the Amphitheater

name: The Silmarillion
description: Beginning on a juggy sidepull, work through a series of pinches, pockets, and underclings to eventually get stood up in the large heuco. From here, work through a series of sloper and edge holds to the final crimpy rail of the lower section. Power through, and enjoy grabbing the victory jug. Fun climbing awaits you from above as you work towards the anchor, but its not over until its over.Â

name: Where The Boardwalk Ends
description: Pitch 1Â (5.8+): Begin on either the Canyoneering Route or Fissure of Green and climb up the the anchor on the backside of the Superslab Boulder. Belay your party up to the ledge.  Pitch 2Â (5.8): Traverse to the right, leaving the ledge for the exposed upper wall of the amphitheater. Work your way to the large bench formation and clip into the anchor. Bring your party to this ledge. Note, for parties of 3 or more, they will have to tuck themselves under the small roof feature.  Pitch 3 (5.10d): Traverse right for two bolts, Then begin cranking straight up through a bulge. Perform some classic Giant City bulge moves and gain access to a ledge. Pull one more buldge and reach the anchor. Belay you party up from here.  Descent: Either rappel down or walk climbers left and out of the amphitheater.

name: Where The Boardwalk Opens
description: Pitch 1 (5.8+): Begin on either the Canyoneering Route or Fissure of Green and climb up the the anchor on the backside of the Superslab Boulder. Belay your party up to the ledge.  Pitch 2 (5.8): Traverse to the right, leaving the ledge for the exposed upper wall of the amphitheater. Work your way to the large bench formation and clip into the anchor. Bring your party to this ledge. Note, for parties of 3 or more, they will have to tuck themselves under the small roof feature.  Pitch 3 (5.9): Traverse right for one bolt, Then begin cranking straight up through a dihedral. Utilize good holds while protecting the crack to reach the cracks end just below a large ledge. Climb out right and up to top out the ledge and reach the anchor. Belay you party up from here.  Descent: Do Not Rappel! Walk off climbers left and out of the amphitheater.

name: Chris's Climb
description: Climb the face to a small overhang. Very positive holds. Fun route.    Note: not recommended for lead but has been done. Gear is limited and not the best.

name: Stand Table Move
description: Climb up and pull the steeper side of the roof. Throw up and catch yourself on the lower edge of the table. Let your feet cut loose and pull the moves to the top. It is recommended that you belay the route from the top.

name: Devil on a Leash
description: Start with a huge move to small holds, continue out through jug eventually to right hand side pull, stick the swing at the end and top out.

name: Devils Traverse
description: Sit start right facing crack to the right of Pinch Me. Move out to the obvious shelf then traverse left. Same top out at Pinch Me.

name: Gill Roof Traverse
description: Start in corner on left of Leashless Angel. Go right and traverse around roof till you are past the corner then topout. Save some strength, top out is probably the crux.

name: Gill Warm Up
description: Distinct & awkward lowball on the short boulder next to the Gill wall. Hands follow the lip from left to right on good slopers.

name: Leashless Angel
description: Follow long moves on small holds out the roof

name: Pinch Me
description: Begin with a sit start, throw left hand to obvious fat sloppy pinch, stick the match and climb out the roof

name: Standard
description: The obvious jug line on the roof. Start on the jugs at the bottom and work your way from monster jug to monster jug. Top out is crux. Either pull hard up to the horn or move out to the left to pull over the top.

name: Superball
description: Sit start and climb the arete using gastons and pockets, feet like to cut...

name: Brimstone
description: Begin by using the high edge feature, throw to the lip of the boulder.

name: Buzz Arete
description: Sit start and layback the arete, climb through apex and top out. Super slopey and cool. People call this problem V3 but is more likely V4.

name: Jah Arete
description: Start low on the arete. Use the side pull on the right to top out this super tricky problem.

name: Lucifer Squeeze
description: Start with left hand in crack and right hand on Jah Arete, figure it out from here

name: Punch Drunk
description: First and second move

name: Seldom Chance
description: Match hands on good edge with bad feet, make big moves and go up and left.

name: Steve's Satanic Arete
description: Use the high start and climb up the right side of the arete

name: Cluck Catcher
description: Beginning with a left hand on a crimp, and your right hand with fingers stacked in a flaringÂ groove, plant your feet and fire up to the chicken heads. Pull through good holds and exit left or right.Â

name: Goldfish
description: Begin with right hand on side pull in the seam, and left hand in shallow pocket. Throw to the fish head âopen mouthâ hold and work up and left, then top out.

name: Sloper Slapper
description: Begin very low in the good undercling hueco. Throw up to some crimpy holds and work through slopers and edges to finish. A burly move awaits

name: Splitting The Difference
description: This is a cool warm up for the area. Begin low and in pockets. Use the seam and Sloper hold to climb up and leftÂ

name: String Theory
description: Beginning low in the seam, utilize crimps and slopers and side pulls to eventually top out. The struggle is real.Â

name: Even When Wet
description: Sit start in obvious pockets work up to crack feature, heel hook the overhung roof and top out.

name: Medicine Man
description: Sit start. Intermediate jugs exist.

name: Broken English
description: On the left side of the Gill wall, starts in high crimps. Thin face climbing to the top. A rap from the top to clean/inspect holds is probably necessary.

name: Center Line
description: Starts in buckets at eye level, continues through a softball-sized pocket to a highball top-out.

name: Giraffe's Hat
description: This is the highball problem just left of The Streak. Starts in sidepull crimps and climbs through the biggest feature on the wall, a large hueco.

name: Left Arete
description: Sit start with left hand on arete and right hand in first pocket. Compress your way up using the arete and the two big pockets for your right hand.

name: Robo Cop
description: Start low, slap to lip, move out right.

name: The Streak
description: This problem follows a brown streak up the shorter, far-right portion of the wall.

name: Black Hole Theory
description: Sit start on the side pull, and throw for the Hueco. Work through the Hueco and climb up and left to top out

name: Higher Education
description: Begin on the slab and climb out the roof using cool pocketed formations and a sloppy pinch. Topout on ledge around 20ish feet.

name: Teater Totter
description: Starts 8 ft right of Higher Education, sit start on low slopers.

name: Return to Forever "Classic"
description: This is the infamous bouldering traverse problem that lines the lower edge of Shelter 1. This traverse holds three different crux sections. If you can find them, there are no hand rests along the way. This is truly a world class climb.

name: Thackery's Wackery
description: Form the block jug on Makanda Layback traverse left about 6 feet,keeping your feet inches from the ground, then go straight up ending in Open Book Direct's bowling ball pocket.

name: Appleknocker
description: Start on the back obvious feature. Climb out and left to long move.

name: Duraflame
description: Beginning matched on the jug, follow cool edges out roof.    Variation: Start on Sizzler and traverse into Duraflame

name: Peach Valley
description: Start matched on jug rail. Reach to thin flake on roof. Go up.     Variation: Problem can be sit started making it much harder

name: Peach Valley Extension
description: Adds a few really fun moves before linking up with Peach Valley. Start on Duraflame and traverse right into Peach Valley.

name: Peaches and Cream
description: Fun.  Begin matched on Shelf at back of cave.  Work out cave roof on decent edges to jug on lip, avoiding flaking rock to the right(a hold was recently broken).  Exciting and tricky mantle top out up and to left.  Don't be afraid to get your heel over your head!

name: Project V12?
description: Climb out roof on super small holds

name: Sizzler
description: Start on feature. Climb out on small holds. Finish by climbing rail system out and left.

name: Southern Sizzler
description: Start on Duraflame. Once you reach the obvious "positive/pinch/edge hold", move left into Sizzler

name: Candy With Razorblades
description: Sit start on a jug rail and go straight up

name: Grave Digger
description: Climb on line of least resistance

name: Grave Robber
description: Start sitting and move up to a pair of close holds at around face height. Then, move through a few slopey holds to a mono before making a big move up and left. Top out above along path of least resistance.

name: Leather Face
description: Start with right in low pockets. Climb right to small edges.

name: Night Shift
description: Start in Thurmond Problem. Cut right at topout.

name: Night Shift Direct
description: Direct start to Night Shift. Starts right of Thurmond Problem.

name: R.I.P.
description: Low start on flake and reach right to slopey pocket. Move up right.

name: Thurmond Problem
description: Climb straight up on big holds. Head left for the topout.

name: Bug Eyes
description: Start with a thin pinch on left and undercling pockets on right.

name: The Flying Dead
description: Stand Start on flat slopers and dyno to a flat flake. Then pull on good holds to the top.

name: The Millipede
description: Sit Start all the way on the left side of the cave on the Cemetary Wall. Traverse thin crimpy pockets to the right, eventually gaining the holds on Skeleton. Description credit The iLlustrated Man

name: Skeleton
description: Climb the crack by starting in limestone-like pockets.

name: Slab of Meat
description: Climb the left side of the wall. Easy slab as far as Southern Illinois goes.

name: Soot
description: Climb the right side of the wall

name: The Tomb
description: Start below and climb through big hueco feature.

name: Broken
description: Sit start in pockets, climb left and top out in Formaldehyde.

name: Broken Direct
description: Sit Start on obvious jug located in the heart of the cave. Climb up cool edges and finish on Broken. Description credit The iLlustrated Man

name: Cracked Skull
description: Begin on awkward underclings and climb the crack

name: Formaldehyde
description: Starts on the same flat jug as Grey Matter. Traverse pocketed feature up and right.

name: Grey Matter
description: Start on flat jugs. Climb up and left.

name: Hornball
description: Sit start with a long move to the horn.

name: Old Timers
description: Start on low edges. Left and right variations.

name: 911 Arete
description: Climb the sloping arete on the leftside of the boulder. Sustained climbing to a relatively easy topout. Climbs harder than it looks.

name: Far Nearer
description: A surprisingly fun one-mover. Sit-start low on the very obvious smiley crimp and get to the jugs at the lip.

name: Fence Lizard
description: V0 sit start.

name: On the Fence
description: Another fun arete climb! Ascend the small boulder using the arete on the left side. Make sure to not mantle it out too early.

name: Your Body is a Wonderland
description: A lowball traverse problem on perfect stone. From a sit-start on the lowest left side of the boulder, follow the lip of the bloc from left to right. When the holds end, mantle it out.

name: Davey Crockett
description: Start matched on a jug about chest height, climb up the center of the boulder. Sharp pockets at the end, with s slopey topout.

name: The Last Stand
description: A low ball that's pretty much just a topout.

name: One and Done
description: A sweet compression problem with a knee bar and a crux top out.

name: Windfall
description: Starts on positive holds, go up using compression moves to a cruxy top out.

name: 2 Fast 2 Furious
description: to the right of Calypso

name: Atlas
description: start with good, chest height hands. work straight up sidepulls. big jug on left is optional, but not necessary.  small detached boulder on ground is off.

name: Calypso
description: Sit start and slap your way up. Top out seems like the crux.

name: Cerberus
description: Start low on the big ledge and move up the overhanging arete through good slopers and pinches. Top out over the corner where the arete meets the top slab.

name: Ogygia
description: Starts as a sit start and works right.

name: V1
description: climb arete nearest to the path on Atlas

name: V3
description: overhanging face nearest to the trail with fun topout

name: Weight of the World
description: Weight of the World

name: Half wheel
description: Obvious compression/heel hook move leads to a classic sloper's mantle.   Video here at 2:25  vimeo.com/148795707   We climbed this on 02-2015, let me know if I'm wrong about the FA nature of the ascent :)

name: One Beer
description: Start on a good hold at chest height on the left side of the boulder. Move up and left to a large jug and make one more move to the top.

name: One Bourbon
description: Sit start on the left hand side of the boulder. Move up to a good sloping ledge and through sloper pockets to the top out.

name: One Scotch
description: Grab holds at head height in the middle of the face and make a move to the top of the boulder.

name: Plead the Fifth
description: Fun body positioning with a throw to the top and a classic Holies mantle to finish.

name: Pub Crawl
description: Start on One Bourbon and move right across the face. The crux comes at the One Scotch starting holds. Finish as for One Beer.

name: Bio-Terrorism
description: Sit start with your hands on the lowest slopers possible. Climb up using more slopers to a crux, slopey topout!

name: Bio-Terrorism Left
description: Same start as Bio-Terrorism, but when you reach the lip, start moving left, then top out.

name: Infectious
description: sit start and go up along arete

name: Bowfin
description: Start as low as you can on the slopey arÃªte. Traverse right on good holds, then top out.

name: "Aidan's a  P-Box"
description: A short, ugly boulder problem (similar to the first ascentionist), which consists of two moves. Starting on a jug with a right heel hook reach to a bad sloping edge and then do either a big bump to a jug up and right or match, then do the big bump.

name: Between Two Ferns
description: Sit Start on obvious crimper plate/flake feature. Do a big lockoff up and right to some good slopers, fun and casual topout. Wish it were longer!!

name: Brown Cow
description: Fun but contrived. Climbs the obvious brown streak of wall with black speckles. Start on your choice of low start holds (a left hand edge, and a right hand crimp or right hand slopy pinch) with a massive left heel hook. The heel hook ledge is "off" for a hand. Figure out some beta and work your way up powerful sidepull pockets and features to some sharp jugs and a thoughtful topout. Holies V6.

name: Community Service
description: Community Service stars on a left hand pinch and a slopey crimp for the right. Work your way up the boulder using slopers and pinches.

name: Crimpy V1
description: To the Right of "V2 (I)." Starts on a Jug and climbs up and right through crimpy flakes and sidepulls, and eventually a righthand seam. Tops out using a juggy "spearhead" looking hold.

name: Cross and Toss
description: Start in good edges with a big ass right foot down low. Climb left and then up. Heed the name. Do a righthand cross move to a good slot, and then jump out left to a comfortable slopey jug. Big jugs all the way to the top! instant classic. Thanks to Phillip and the ICA for cleaning off all of these old classics!!!

name: Daisy Dukes
description: Fun climbing on cool edge features to a high right hand gaston finger bucket and a fun topout. Starts on the ledge features which is used as a heelhook on Brown Cow.

name: Dirty Water Dog
description: On the first boulder at the Brown Cow Boulder. Traverse left from the farthest right sit start holds to the V2 (I) and top out as such. A good warm up.

name: Don't Feed the Plants!
description: Fun little warmup on good slopey edges. Farthest right line on the backside of the Brown Cow boulder. Short but sweet.

name: Feed Me, Seymore
description: Start in slopers at chest height and traverse right through more slopers to a somewhat dirty topout. Fun, just needs more traffic. Walk right to get off the boulder.

name: The Fisherman, right variation
description: The starting section has a fun sequence moving through big holds. Easy topout.

name: The Fisherman
description: The first route on the next boulder if heading right up the trail from Sukha. The sloper up and right of the first crimp on the face looks good, but is practically useless; bumping your left hand up the rail is the better option.

name: Helios
description: Sit Start on two 1 pad crimp/seam/edges and either go out left to a pinch on the arete and then head up, or do a big left hand move straight up to a good rail. Juggy topout.

name: Ovaltine
description: Start on low jug undercling and do a big move up and right, out of the overhang to a good edge. Match the edge and finish on jugs. Crux is not draggin yo azz on da ground.

name: Pickles
description: Tall face to the right of Brown Cow. Start on high start holds and climb up the featured wall.

name: Sukha
