description: Really fun!! Classic Holy Boulders Slopey Jugs to a hard topout. Starts directly to the left of the arete on the Brown Cow Face.    super fun and easy dyno eliminates can be done on this climb if you're into that :) d

name: Sukha Sit
description: Dig hard on that heel and follow the bad slopers up and right to the start of Sukha stand. Start hold tends to be wet for a while after a good rain.

name: V0 Crack
description: Short and Dirty Crack on the right side of the first boulder you come to at the Brown Cow Area

name: V1
description: Good but short. Sit Start on the farthest right side of the first boulder in the Brown Cow Area, on small edges. Climb up the seams and edges to juggy top out.

name: V2 (I)
description: Left most (of the good climbs) on the first boulder. Goes up the center of the wall utilizing two big sloping square pinch features. Tops out up and left.

name: Vintage Vice
description: Fun little problem on the left side of the Brown Cow Boulder. Jugs to a fun topout.

name: Brown Recluse
description: From a sit-start just left of the middle of the face on a right hand sloper hueco, and a left hand juggy hueco, climb left and then upwards on cool sloping jugs. Move out right for first crux move before finally heading straight up and left on fingery holds to the scary and difficult topout.

name: Cripps
description: This thing is absolutely crazy! You begin under a short roof, get set up on a couple crimps and do a huge dyno to a sloper. Then work up using the slopers, a mono, and a heel-toe cam. The second crux is throwing to the lip. After this you top out on about 10 feet of slab, 20 feet off the ground.

name: Twin Eagles
description: Climb up the large water groove, using slopers and pockets. Crux is near the top.

name: Bubble Wrap
description: Start low on a thin rail and a right undercling, bust through the opening move and continue up the face to the easier top-out.

name: Hourglass
description: Start low and work your way up using slopey pinches. The topout is probably the hardest part.

name: Pomona Animal Society
description: Start in the cut out part of the boulder, then figure some way to get your feet up onto the slab part.

name: Chernobyl
description: Start matched in crimpy hueco, post your feet, then go for the lip. The topout is the hardest part!

name: Enlightenment
description: This is the first boulder you will come upon in the Illuminati sector. Climb the rounded arÃªte utilizing slopers jugs as pinches. Sit start low and slightly right on arÃªte with big feet. The crux is the topout. Enjoy

name: Jungle Book
description: Classic overhung arete madness on the leftside of the New Zero Boulder. start on the left of the arete on jugs climb up aways till the holds disappear then do a large, but static move to a sloper on the arete. Slot a toe-hook then match the sloper. Cut your feet and enjoy the ride. Stick the crazy swing and then campus the final moves to a hard but manageable topout. Absolutely hyper-classic

name: King's High
description: Tall but doable. Start on a large undercling sidepull jug feature and work up and slightly right. Crux is a long move to a gaston from a small 2-3 finger right hand gaston. high as hell, proud.

name: Michael Jordan
description: The amazing looking sloper problem to the left of Crimson Flower. Sit Start down and right in the "Air Jordan" feature. Make a big move up and left and then work through the slopey feature to reach a bad right hand crimp. Make a huge dyno move off of this crimp to a hold over the lip. Hard, scary mantle.

name: The New Zero
description: THE testipece of the Holy Boulders. Jason was shown this line when it was dubbed "fatty sloper action" and devoted his time to be rewarded the FA of the best line at the Holies. Start down and right on the arete jug and move up and left through horrible slopers to a hard heel hook or hop move at the lip. absolutely gorgeous climb on sticky holds with perfect Fontainebleau friction, and features.

name: Onyx
description: Start directly to the left of Enlightenment. Stand Start on two holds at chest height. A right hand sidepull, pockety fingerlock thing, and a left hand pinch. Hard move going left to a pinch, go right to a sloper, then duckbill crimp, then top out. Two topouts are often done. If you traverse right into enlightenment, it feels morelike v6, but the original way stays straight, and avoids all the holds on enlightenment. This way probably clocks in around v7.

name: The Order of Mirth
description: Begin on a sloper, pull a couple lock off moves, then cruzer at the top.

name: The Realm
description: Same start as Running with Scissors, but cut right when you reach the seam heading to the right side of the boulder.

name: Reptilian Shapeshifter
description: Sit Start as for Michael Jordan, pick your ass up and traverse rightwards into Crimson Flower via a somewhat cryptic sequence and finish as for Trillium.The irony wonât be lost on cultured individuals (such as those reading this no doubt) that Reptilian Shapeshifter is the BONAFIDE Trillium Sit Start, whereas Crimson Flower is merely a LOW start to Trillium, rather than being aÂ true SIT as often described. Avoiding the dab plays into the difficulty a bit, but not as much as it might seem at first glance. All in all, this is a worthy goal for those whoâre at the point where running laps on Trillium is childâs play, but whoâve long since realized that this gets them no closer to a send of the intimidating Michael Jordan. Real Ballers might even use this as a stepping stone to MJ...

name: Running with Scissors
description: Line to the right of Undercling King. Start in front of a large tree. Climbs the obvious left angling feature. the moves to the top are relatively easy, then the heat comes,, watch out for that tree ;) Running with scissors... you're not SUPPOSED to do it.    ***EDIT***    Since being posted, the tree has been removed and the landing cleaned... Scissorless Running

name: Treehugger
description: Dont know who put it up, and fairly certain it has never been repeated. Climb the water groove directly left of the tree, and to the right of trillium.

name: Trillium
description: Starts on a left hand 3 finger pocket (four for some) and a right hand slopey slot. Utilize either a hard to place heel-toe cam or a bad smear to get to an iron crimp feature. Slopers, sidepulls, and crimps lead you to a hard topout.

name: Trillium Sit
description: Adds two moves. Low start with right hand slopey hueco sidepull, and left hand hueco sidepull. Left foot either toe hook or heel-toe cam. Climb up the slightly overhung wall utilizing slopers, pockets, crimps and a second heel-toe cam. Cruxy top-out. Sometimes also known as "Crimson Flower"

name: Undercling King
description: Start on two wide sidepull crimps, and drop into a right hand crimp. Then climb straight up the technical face... (look for that undercling!) a committing last throw to a jug in order to avoid dabbing/crashing through the  tree. Crux is making the stab into the slot at mid height. Some use the thin undercling, others go big...  Absolutely classic.. Enjoy.

name: Abra
description: The slab along the arete to the left of Presto. This is also the (scary)Â downclimb for Presto.

name: All that Glitters
description: Start on two good side pulls to the left of Bangin Blood. Climb up using some nasty slopers.

name: Avant Gardener
description: Climb up tall featured slab. The crux is at the beggening.

name: B-Cup
description: Start low on sloper, throw for the boob, then pull to the lip.

name: Bangin Blood
description: Start on flake, pull over arete to crimps and top out.

name: Bangin Blood Direct
description: Same start as Bangin Blood, but go directly up instead of using the crimps out right.

name: Bill Cosby
description: Start matched on the large hole, move out left to the arete, and top out.

name: Bourbon Shooter
description: Start low with left hand in a two finger pocket and right hand on a pinch. Huck to the lip and mantle.

name: Bubbles
description: Work your way up the face using pockets.

name: Fightin' Words
description: Start low, with right hand at the end of the pockety feature, and left hand on pinch. Huck for the lip, then mantle.

name: Full Grain
description: Start towards the bottom left of the slab, hand(s) in a slopey dish. Continue straight up the slab until the crux at the lip, don't slip!

name: Have It
description: You better keep your core tight if you want to finish this one. Have It starts with your left hand in a pocket and right on the arÃªte. Work your way up the arÃªte using smears and balance. The finish move is the crux.

name: Jump for Jesus
description: Start on two opposing crimpy side pulls, dyno to the lip and top out.

name: The Lemon of Pink
description: A tall slab with a little dyno with decent holds.

name: Light as a Feather
description: Start in the middle left of the face, then work your way up and to the left to the arÃªte using crimps.

name: Presto
description: Begin a few feet to the right of the arete. Climb up the slab face using good feet and a crimp near the top. Arete is off.

name: Puddin Pops
description: Start sitting down, climb up on good holds.

name: Push Up
description: Start low and to the right of the start for B-Cup. Pull the first move to the start of B-Cup, then throw for the arÃªte to finish.

name: Rose Gold
description: Same start as B-Cup, but go up to the pinch with your right hand instead. Use a toe hook to pull a rose move to the top.

name: Shoot at the Hip
description: Start low, with right hand on the arÃªte, left hand on anything you can grab. Stand up to a small left hand crimp, get a higher right foot and shoot for the lip.

name: Stand Up to the Left
description: For this problem you're going to start on the left bigger hueco on the big slab face. Once you have your hands in it, start traversing left and up to a committing last move.

name: Stand Up to the Right
description: Start on a side pull around head height, get a smear and pull up to a bad right hand side pull. Hand-foot match, and stand up.

name: Suede
description: A slab problem using the right arÃªte of the Full Grain boulder.

name: Tabernacle
description: Climb the finger crack that splits the face like an exponential decay function through a graph. Sit start low on the crack and finesse your way up with toe jams, gastons, and laybacks.

name: V6
description: Start on high ledge, pull move into large flake and climb up.

name: Boomer
description: start on horizontal finger cracks at chest high to the left of con artist, work straight up crimps on short problem. This was formerly mis-named as âEl Pintoâ , but it was an unnamed V1 from the comp.Â

name: Con Artist
description: Start on your choice of very poor slopey slot crimps and head straight up the short slabby face. Hard move off bad left hand crimp. Deceivingly hard. Selected quotes: "Oh, that'll go next go for sure." "That was so close!" "Maybe next trip..."

name: El Pinto
description: Sit start on some bad feet and a sloping crimp in the middle of the boulder. Make a strong move up to jugs for an easy topout. The V1 next to con artist was perviously misnamed as âEl Pinto.âÂ

name: Lowrider
description: Sit start on great jug and okay feet. Follow obvious jugs. Great sloper to left of the small crack and a good lefthand sidepole on the left edge make for a clean topout.

name: Lowrider Traverse
description: You'll have lots of options to go up and down the rails that run this side of the boulder, but a lot of the holds are junk. Give it a feel before jumping on. Good warm-up.

name: The Mollusk
description: Follow the very obvious line that goes along the slopey scoop on the right side of the boulder. The classic warm-up of the Holies.

name: Variations
description: The back of the Mollusk boulder is littered with a large amount of holds, most being very positive. There are many variations that exist. Traversing from left to right (and back again as much as you please) is a great way to get warm on some great feeling holds.

name: Double Rainbow
description: Start low on pockets, traverse up right and top out behind the tree.

name: Flugelhorn
description: Short, steep, pinches & compression on the far right side of the boulder.

name: Gatekeeper
description: Sit-start to Open Gates. Starts in the hueco down and right. Getting of the ground is the crux. Lift off the ground using mental fortitude that your bicep doesn't burst and fall into a slopey crimp. Get a heel toe cam in the hueco and reach up for a weird 2-3 finger sideways pocket. lock that off to the crimp on open gates, busting left to the pinch and throw to the finish.    I've searched for a first ascentionist to what I thought was an obvious problem. The only thing i have found is that Luke Parady may have done this problem many many years ago but the person was unsure. So if anyone knows, I'm all ears!

name: Kung Fury
description: Kung Fury has the same start as Flugelhorn, but instead of topping out directly up, you move left behind the tree on small sharp crimps.

name: Open Gates
description: Sit start on the far left side of the overhang. Crux is a fun dyno off a left-hand pinch.

name: Vomitorium
description: We started seated off a right handed crimp with a left heel hook, and moved up onto slopers before continuing left towards flugelhorn's topout. Finishes with a fun mantle. It's a pretty fun lowball sloper battle and figured more people aught to try it out.   Name is just something fun we thought of and the grade is a guess. This line was already pretty clean so I assume it has been done before by someone. I figured I would go ahead and post it here, but if you have any information on it then please let me know.Â

name: Anthrax ArÃªte
description: A beautiful tall, slabby arÃªte.

name: Aquaculture
description: Start on a low undercling with your left hand and a side pull with your right hand. Pull two moves to the jug on Narwhal.

name: Darkside
description: Starting standing on a left hand undercling and a right hand crimp, do two hard bump moves to reach your right hand to the lip of the boulder. Fun and tricky mantle to put you on top. Cool holds and movement, but a bit too lowball to be a classic.

name: The Elitist
description: The usually dirty face to the left of Platypus

name: The Lesser Line
description: Starting seated, reach to a friendly crimp with your left hand and leap to a very positive edge above the lip of the boulder with your right hand. Mantle it out. A fun jump, albeit not the biggest dyno in the world.

name: Moon Boots
description: Far left, low sit start on short problem

name: Narwhal
description: Start on a big jug, then cross with your left to a interesting pinch and find a way to reach the top of the boulder.

name: Platypus
description: The Square arete on the far right side of the Public Enemy Boulder. Starts on two slopers and does a big move up and left, then another bump with the left hand. A strange three finger undercling/sidepull pinch at the lip leads to a jump to a 45 sloper. Unique top out.

name: Public Enemy
description: Variations exist for the Start. Either very low on juggy pinches and huecos, or slightly higher on slopey-er pinches. Either go straight up or up and left. Grade depends on these factors, but basically falls withing the V1-V2 range.

name: Saccharine Crack
description: Start deep in the cave with both hands in the hand jam section. Work out the cave using fingerlocks, smears, and brute strength. Pull the bulge and finish in the massive hueco for a nice sit down finish (or top out the tall fist crack).

name: Sad Tilly
description: Fun slab to pass the time and work on some good feet.Â

name: Son of the Morning
description: Start on the far right side of the arÃªte in the scoop feature. Follow the crimp seam to a left side pull and a deep pocket jug. Continue on bad slopers all the way to the corner and top out on better holds. High right heels the whole way.

name: V7
description: Between Inspector Gadget and Darkside is this tricky one mover. Start standing with your left hand in a small undercling pocket and right on an awful crimp. Pull onto the wall and smack the lip of the boulder. Move left a bit onto some more positive slopers to top out.

name: Armageddon 5000
description: Start low on two jugs, throw a heel toe cam in, match the left and work your way through a series of pinches and slopers. This problem isn't over till you've topped it out.

name: Big D
description: This is a link up of Red Sea into Big Mitch.  Sit Start as per Red Sea, but instead of topping out once you get the giant sidepull jug after the hard bit of Red Sea, continue rightwards and slightly down into the start of Big MItch and then finish as per that problem.  I doubt this is a First Ascent, but posting it as such is the most surefire way to get a discussion going about it. Who did this first, what did they name it, and what was their grade opinion?

name: Big Meech
description: Start on horiztanal holds with hands crossed, then reach up to the seem to the left, paste your foot and fight your way up using nasty slopers.

name: Big Mitch
description: Start matched on a pedestal ledge, climb right on good edges, finish it off with a large throw to a good sloper.

name: Bigger D
description: This is a link up of Moses into Big Mitch.  Sit Start as per Moses, but instead of topping out once you get the giant sidepull jug, Â continue rightwards and slightly down into the start of Big MItch and then finish as per that problem.  Just as with "Big D" I doubt this is a First Ascent, but posting it as such is the most surefire way to get a discussion going about it. Who did this first, what did they name it, and what was their grade opinion?

name: Cain and Ankle
description: Sit start and climb up slopey rail using some crimps out left.

name: King Solomon
description: Based on "Secrets of So iLL" video: Start in middle of the wall and dyno to gaston-jug (crux). Lower start on crimps may exist.

name: Moses
description: Moses starts on a horizontal edge/pinch to the right of Red Sea. Move left to a crimp and then pull a large lock off move to intersect with Red Sea. Finish up on Red Sea.

name: The Red Sea
description: start low and left. make a few moves on whatever holds feel best to a hard move to gain a good hold in the middle of the face.  keep moving right then up the heady, somewhat slopey topout

name: See No Evil
description: Same start as Red Sea, but go directly up the arete.

name: Unnamed V1
description: Climb up the last seam to the right of Big Meech to the positive ledges and the classic slopey topout.

name: [Redacted]
description: Starting on two strange slopey holds, pull onto the wall and lock a heel-toe cam. Work upwards on crimpers to a slightly high top out.

name: Comfortably Numb
description: Follow a line of small, sharp crimps up the slabby face. Could have more stars if the holds felt a bit better to hold...

name: Comfortably Numb Arete
description: Start standing on slopers, follow the slopey lip about halfway across the entire face and then mantle. Poor feet.

name: The Crooked Master
description: Starting on a very awful looking hold, follow nearly non-existing holds slightly left and upwards. I do not know very much info about this route, and as far as I know it is unrepeated. Another twisted boulder problem from the mind of Kehl...

name: Evil Empire
description: A tall proud line. Begin on the middle of the face and work your way up the wall using positive crimps. You may want to try the moves on a rope first, the crux is at the top.

name: Fat Lip
description: A compression problem that goes up between Tennis Shoe Arete and KFC. Go to the pocket with your right, then climb up the two arete features.

name: Kangarete
description: This may have been an FA as I've never heard any talk about this climb, but it seems too obvious to not have ever been done. Name is what my buddies and I have always called it. Climbs the obvious arete to the right of The Other Axis on sharp holds. Hang and drop when the holds get really juggy. Dirtyish...

name: KFC
description: Move through good holds until you can get your right hand on the faint, slopey arete. Work your way through this cool feature to the easy top out. Short but sweet.

name: The Other Axis
description: An interesting slab problem revolving around one difficult move. Start standing on a thin left hand iron crimp and right hand broken sidepull. Work upwards on small holds to a very long lock-off. Continue towards the jugs near the top of the wall. Hang and drop from the jugs at around 15 feet. The rock is pretty but a bit brittle. Be careful!

name: Reflection of a Man
description: On the face opposite Shadow of a Man, start on the semi-circle crimps and move up to the small, crimpy seam. Make a long move right to the bread loaf. Stand up to the slopey rail and bump to the sloped side pull. Arete is off until the top out near Tennis Shoe Arete.  A traverse is also possible all the way to KFC/Fat Lip...who's gonna link it??

name: Seafoam Arete
description: Follow the slopey arete to the top of the boulder.

name: Seams Easy
description: Follow the thin seam to the top-out. Crux is about mid-way up.

name: Secret of Davenport
description: Start sitting quite low on the center of the Shadow of a Man face. Follow small crimps left and up slightly. Slap the lip and do a weird mantle about five feet above the ground. Not the best problem at the Holies, but cool holds. I climbed this thinking it was an FA and gave it this name. Dave Chancellor has since told me it has been done, but he says he cannot recall the name, so we will just go with this.

name: Shadow of a Man
description: One of the best of the grade the Holies has to offer. Starting on a low jug, move up to a slopey sidepull, do some magic with your feet and reach your left hand up to a bad crimp. Get your feet up, and do a tricky move to a blocky jug in the middle of the face.

name: Shadow of a Man Sit
description: For the sit start, begin several feet to the right of the normal start for Shadow. Pull a large first move to some crimps, then traverse left into the start for Shadow of a Man.

name: Shadow of Davenport
description: Start on Shadow of a Man, traverse left and finish on Secret of Davenport. I've heard that this is the same grade as Secret of Davenport, but I disagree. Plus it heads a few cool moves!     P.S. You can also try to do the sit start to Shadow of a Man, and then connect that into Shadow of Daventport. FA may still be up for grabs!?

name: Tennis Shoe Arete
description: Start on edges on the arete do a long reach, followed by another long reach up and left. Easy top out, but not a great fall if you blow it.

name: V2 Slab
description: Start on two matched pockets and move up the slab on sparse holds and kind of bad feet. The topout is a little tough.

name: Vulture Fest
description: Work your way up a tall slab that leads to a commuting mantle up high.

name: Worm's End
description: Climb Worm's Way to the jug, but rather than hanging and dropping, follow a line of crimps to the top of the wall and top out. Might be nice to have these moves dialed in just in case you send Worms Way and have a bit more juice left at the jug. Would be easy to climb up the jug feature to work the crimp moves.

name: Worm's Way
description: From a sit start, traverse right on a series of poor pinches to a really large move to gain the huge swooping jug feature. Using the jug swoop, do a sequence that clocks in around v3 and hang and drop at the large circular jug.

name: Worm's Way Stand
description: Start at the beginning of the arching rail feature and climb up the "worm" through jugs and slopers with helpful heel hooks to keep you from cutting feet. Finish on the large jug at the end of the rail.

name: Austin's Arete
description: The start to this problem is down low, on a right hand pinch and a left hand crimp. The first move is the crux, and you need to be careful to not dab on the boulder behind you. Fun arete climb.

name: Fire Up the Barbie
description: Start matched on a large flake and cross into an interesting plated-mushroom hold on the roof then move out the the large, positive sloper to the right. Establish on the sloper and move up through your choice of pockets and other holds to a jug and following top out.

name: Glutes Are Aid
description: Climb the offwidth chimney on the warm-up boulder. Shimmy your way up to the lip without using the arete.

name: Hot Rats
description: Start matched on two crimps down low. Pull some moves to get out to the arete out left. Same finish as Stilleto.

name: Stiletto
description: Start on head-high jugs, heel and cross up and right to some smaller holds. Then toss to the lip, mantle, and scramble to the top.

name: Sweet As, Man
description: Start low on a flat shelf and climb up through a flake and some positive slopers to an even more slopey top-out slab. Finesse your body over the bulge and finish your way up the delicate top section.

name: Battle For Endor
description: Climb using thin horizontal seam to reach the right side of the Death Star. Climb to the top from here.

name: Boba Fett
description: Start on the right side of the boulder pulling on crimps. Make a long reach to good holds and continue to the top.

name: Death Star Center
description: Pull using good holds to reach the Death Star. Continue up and through the middle of the Death Star

name: Emperors New Groove
description: Use good holds to reach the top

name: No Disintegrations
description: Climb using good hold to the top

name: That's No Moon
description: Climb using thin horizontal seams to reach the top

name: There Is No Try
description: Start on good horizontal seams, get your feet set and make a long reach to a good hold. Continue using horizontal seams to reach the top.

name: Rotel
description: Get to the holds up above your head using the large steps on the left side of the boulder. Establish yourself, get a high heel, and go for the big slot up high.

name: Texas Revolution
description: Texas Revolution starts near the middle of the boulder, on the monster jug. Walk your feet up to get hold of the small left hand crimp, get your feet up, and do a dead point to the high right hand crimp. Get hold of a left hand, get your feet up, and launch for a hold near the top. This is a tall man problem unfortunately.

name: TexMex
description: Start on big holds around chest height, use good feet and good holds to get up.

name: The First Rule
description: Climb the arete to the left of grade school starting on a jug at head height.

name: Grade School
description: Start on 2 big undercling jugs at the start of the horizontal crack. Cruise over on juicy underclings and follow the left leaning crack up. At the top, grab a slopey hueco in the big cut out, get a high foot, and reach up to nice jugs above the bulge to an nice top out

name: Marla
description: Starting sitting the same as Tyler Durden, cut left and move to a good pocket and do a large move to a jug. From here, go straight up and somehow execute a tricky, dirty and scary mantel off not good holds. Be mindful of the slightly sketchy flake out left. AKA "Marla and the Tree," for reasons that may be obvious when you arrive at the problem.

name: Odd Job
description: Start on two underclings under the bulge. Work your way up to the next slopers and guck for a slopey edge up high. The boulder to the right is off.

name: Robert Paulson
description: Start standing on an undercling and reach back to one of a couple good sloping holds near the back of the boulder. You may have to hop a bit to reach the hold. Top out. Small, short and sweet.

name: Tyler Durden
description: From a sit start on two juggy holds, work upwards utilizing either a long pull off a small gaston or a big throw to a sloping jug off a crimp near the gaston. Grab a near the top of the boulder before slapping back to another sloper. From here, move right to a good sloping feature and top out. There is a variation that begins on Tyler Durden that cuts left and moves back right to join the top of Durden, and it is around the same difficulty.

name: V2
description: Unnamed V2 from the comp. Sit start on the obvious jug/flake. Climb up pinchesÂ on the arete to a juggy topout.

name: V4
description: Unnamed problem from the comp.Â Sit start with hands on a slanted crimpy flake. Smear right foot in the dish and choose 1 of the 2 foot nubs for your left foot. Traverse right along the lower ledge using crimps, a sloper, and a heel hook or two. Lip/top of the boulder is off until the topout at the first crack on the lip. Casual topout on jugs after that.

name: Cracked Shell
description: Start low on jug and throw to crimp ledge. Match and fight through slopers to finish.

name: Embryo Shell
description: Start as per Embryostasis, but continue left out of the embryo feature into the slopey topout of Cracked Shell.

name: Embryo Stasis
description: Start low on pointed jug, climb up through the "embryo" and topout through the thin seam.

name: Empty Nest Syndrome
description: Start on flakey jug, then work your way up using slopers.

name: Free Hugs
description: Begin on good holds low and to the right of the arete feature. Climb through the arete to a hold in the seam. Top out to the left from there.

name: Peace Pipe
description: Start on jug rail to the right of embryo stasis. Traverse right to the arete, climb up and top out.

name: Finger/Hand Crack
description: A nice(although short) line that starts as fingers and gets gradually wider after a small ledge. There are a few face holds to pull on when the crack turns to wide hands near the top.

name: Fist crack
description: Awkward moves in a short fist crack lead to a ledge underneath a roof. Once you figure out how to stand up underneath the roof, one kind-of-airy move will get you above it, then a short army crawl will put you in reach of the anchors.

name: Wide crack
description: Some nice feet on the arete of the crack wall at the beginning peter out a third of the way to make for a pretty blank extended crux that ends with a difficult mantle. A couple of easier moves for a second mantle will get you up to the anchors.    Definitely requires solid off-width technique. Long sleeves recommended.

name: The Grand Traverse
description: A traverse from the right side of the cave to the top left. Crossover through shelves and jugs to the same topout as Warm Up v2. Can be done when flooded - just expect to get soaked if you fall!

name: Warm Up
description: Move up steep terrain on nice holds to a dirty topout. From the starting holds, move up and right to the nice jug shelf, them work up left to the top.   Can be with a stand start when flooded.

name: Beached Whale
description: Sit start, just follow the crack to the top. Easy to avoid the moss. Just a couple moves to reach the top. Fun for an outdoor beginner! There are some loose holds, but they seem locked in there for the most part. Top is basically covered by a growing sapling, which leads to a less-than-attractive topout. Hence the name...

name: Dog Rock - Ear Scratchies
description: Start off like Ear Scratchies, but instead of topping out tragedy to the right, use crack along the ear to fully top out. Â I didn't get to work this much, it should send but it was the end of our day and I was beat. Â This would need to be brushed before anyone tries. Â When we get back out I'll update this to it being cleaned. (also I have no idea what grade this will be so the 0+ is a place holder)

name: Dog Rock - Neck Scratchies
description: start on the ArÃªte with your left hand, right on a crimp, feet in the bottom corner.Â  Finish sitting on the ledge.

name: Dogmouth
description: Start on Dog Rock and traverse on the cliff towards Motormouth and Valpo. Finish on Motor mouth finish.

name: Dumpy
description: Dont touch the face to the left of the route

name: El Jefe
description: Bottom 6 feet are chill, getting up on the face over the roof is a little tricky (big roof),Â crux is on the top face.

name: Lilâ Boi
description: Starting with left hand on solid jug on left side of the face, right hand on right face, heel hook with left foot and right foot underneath the boulder. Â Work around to the left and top out with the more than solid holds. Â Could work into an easy traverse as well.

name: Mosquito Bite
description: Start on the side pull/rail around chest level. Finish by matching on the underside of the roof (there are no holds, press into it).     Move up using crimps and jugs/rails. Crux is the first sequence of moves on the route. After the initial sequence of crimps it is nothing but jugs/rails.

name: Motormouth
description: Same dihedral as Valpo, but on the left corner instead of the right.Â

name: Old Man Face Warm-ups
description: This wall is the same as the Valpo Problem, just to the right of it. Â The rock looks like it has a face in it. Â The problem starts to the right of the wall, with a pinch and a ledge. Â You have a few options from there, 2 follow out towards Valpo and finish where Valpo does/top out, and the third goes straight up and tops out.I would recommend getting on top of the problem and cleaning off the top out, it's a tad of a mess and I didn't have the stuff to clean it up wellÂ

name: Once Knew A Boy From Oglesby
description: Sit start on back left side of the left face of the prow. Work right toward the tree and then go to the top of the boulder.

name: Once Knew A Girl From Oglesby
description: Sit start on right side of the boulder. Move out to the nose of the prow and then climb over the top.

name: Valpo
description: Start with hands going low left around the face of the dihedral. Work the jugs up until you step onto the ledge above.

name: Zach's Graduation
description: Start sitting down on the left side. Keep left hand on left side and work right hand up. Coming over the top is the crux.

name: Boneyard
description: Hard starting holds making this problem tough right from the start. Start at bottom left of the boulder and work your way right to the right side top. Top out is a little tricky also. A good lowball with a few power moves

name: Essential Business
description: Start all the way to the left underside the boulder. Traverse right on the rail using heel and toe hooks until there are no more good holds. The main crux is a long reach into a small crimp with the right hand - using a bad bicycle, cross underneath and match with the left hand. Then reach around the lip with the right to link up with Reach Around and finish.

name: Jamie's Traverse
description: This is just to the LEFT of the Mushroom Slab, it's a traverse, not super hard but has a couple less then great crimps.

name: Main Street Blues
description: Awkward low sit start with both hands in the blast hole. Move straight up. Can fire directly for the lip of the boulder or use small intermediate crimps in between blast hole and lip.

name: Mushmom
description: Crux is the first move. Â Sit start on the shallow pinch block, getting as much opposition as possible off the good foot hold. Â Power up to the shelf, keeping core tension to avoid dabbing the other boulder. Â There are several ways to to the slab. Â I make a somewhat big move up to the good sloper in the middle of the lip, but there are various smaller crimps near the base of the slab or immediately below the lip to use as well. Â Maintain tension to cross over your right hand to the good jug crimps above the sloper, match, then bump right hand up to another good jug crimp, and come into another good incut jug crimp to the left of your right hand. Â Do what you need to to rock up on a foot and lean forward onto the slab, then walk up. Â This route is technically an eliminate, since you cannot use the good jug shelves to the right or left of the slab on this line, however, it still works well because the slab is so large. Â More like avoiding temptation to use them than actually avoid them. Â The stand start begins on the jug shelf and goes at V5 or so.

name: Mushroom Slab
description: Start the problem on the jug rail under the slab and throw for the lip. Then follow the ladder of holds up the left to the top.

name: Oscar the Grouch
description: Start on an left undercling and a right sidepull. Pull through using bad holds and solid feet. The crux is going around the corner. Finish on Trashcan.

name: Pale King
description: Sit start matching on crimp just left of the blast hole, work slightly right on crimps to center lip top out of the boulder.

name: Reach Around
description: Starting with both hands on the pocket rail underneath. Work out right and then up the rail on top of the boulder's face.

name: Shotgun Love Songs
description: Low sit start work left up a series of crimps.

name: Snapping Turtle Traverse
description: Start underneath the boulder on marked holds & traverse left using toe and heel hooks. Throw blind around the lip and finish on Turtle Head traverse.Â

name: Swamp Ass Season
description: Great roof problem with potential for extending a hard sit start and other variations. Work the obvious line out to the right.

name: Tinkering Toward Utopia
description: Sit start on the low right side of the rail and work left toward center top out.

name: Trashcan Boulder
description: fun compression start into a one move dyno to the lip of the boulder. The feet make this boulder the challenging part. Brownie points if you lap this right after you send the mushroom slab.

name: Turtle head traverse
description: Great feet throughout. Start on the far left with two good handholds move to the right to a big jug match then over to a decent crimp Â match crimp (the Crux) then a couple good hand holds to the top!

name: Turtle Spider
description: Start on the same holds as Reach Around, but go straight up the face without using any holds on the arete. Â The crux involves rocking over your foot on a good foothold at the base of the head wall and balancing to stand up. Â There is alot of growth on the face, but all the necessary holds are clean and not lost within the greenery.

name: The twist and shout
description: A little unnecessary but hey it's fun to spin around!

name: All Bark, No Bite
description: This is a good ol' verticle line up the wall. it features a solid landing and some fun moves. a good route for a beginner trying to get out of their comfort zone. Top out!!!  Start left with right hand on side pull and left hand on edge. Move right and up the line.  Avoid choss on the left and ledge on the right.

name: Connor's Crack / Keaney's Wall
description: Very fun highball! Start on face left of the crack for decent holds. Move up and right into crack. - V2 Go straight up the crack. - V3 Avoid the jutting forehead on the right. Finish up the top nose for a slightly sketchy highball topout ;)  Rock is very secure here. Landing isn't the best. If you plan on topping out, go round n check out the top first.

name: Pike
description: BEWARE THE PIKE! This is a real bad boy. You can identify by the pike shaped impression on the left of the route, and by the spike of doom below... Moderately easy; a few little slopey holds/ insecure crimps. Crux is a few committing moves leading to a scary and insecure topout. Avoid choss to left and right of route. rock is solid in the middle.  BE ADVISED There is a broken wooden post threatening to impale any would-be senders who happen to fall far enough to land on it. Fr tho stick a crash pad on it (or chop it down :). Pro tip - go round and brush the top before topping out.

name: Green
description: This is one of the only actual boulders in the park suitable for climbing. This Green guy is coated in moss which is easy to clean off. The obvious line has been cleaned but may require touching up. Start low left and work your way over the bulge to top out.

name: Red Rocket
description: A Beautiful feature with some nice jugs. Start left where the bottom of the cliff meets the earth and work your way up and slightly right. Finish is the top of the rock.

name: Broken Link
description: beta pending

name: Buck Naked
description: beta pending

name: Decapitator
description: Large Chimney all the way up.  Classic ROute in MP.

name: Demitri's Demise
description: beta pending

name: Double Overhang aka Fourth Crack
description: Bouldery overhang start to easier moves.

name: First Crack
description: Crack and dihedral system to the right of Blank Wall.

name: Graduation Day
description: beta pending

name: Monkey Swing
description: beta pending

name: Mud Crack
description: beta pending

name: Nosey
description: A moderately laid back arete and face route.  Crux is early.

name: Primak's Peril
description: beta pending

name: Purgatorio
description: The crux is on the left side of the boulder it's a solid three finger pocket.    Mainly a lot of crips and pockets.    Watch out for spiders!    Feet placement is critical if you want to stay on the boulder.

name: Quadrangle Traverse
description: beta pending

name: Riverview Ridge
description: Nose/arÃªte around the corner from Double Overhang.  Follow the nose all the way up, but watch the spiders.  Crux is about a quarter of the way up, where handholds get marginal so you have to just hug the arÃªte and high-step it.  The exposure and views are pretty amazing, and it's also a wonderful photo opportunity...

name: Second Crack aka Myrtle's Folly
description: Climb the wide crack and face on the left.

name: Sentinel Chimney
description: Climb the chimney from the Cove (East) side of the Sentinel. Escape right to the north face near top and avoid the block on the South tower of the sentinel.

name: Sentinel East Face
description: The easy laidback east face of Sentinel Tower.  Massive jugs and ladder-like climbing.  Crux is probably the top-out move.

name: Son of Godzilla
description: beta pending

name: Spinal Compression
description: beta pending

name: Turtles for Peace
description: beta pending

description: beta pending

description: beta pending

description: beta pending

description: beta pending

description: beta pending

description: beta pending

description: beta pending

description: beta pending

description: beta pending

description: beta pending

name: J. Stettner's Friction Pitch
description: beta pending

name: Labyrinth
description: beta pending

name: Park Avenue
description: beta pending

name: Sky Walk
description: beta pending

name: Sleeper
description: beta pending

name: Sundance
description: beta pending

name: That Boy is Still Up There Squealing Tires
description: beta pending

name: Whippoorwill Hollow Crack
description: beta pending

name: Access Route
description: Climb the east face on easy ledges just left of the large tree.

name: Devious
description: It's not as straightforward as it seems to be! Climb straight up the ridge.

name: Grisly
description: Start in the center of the face, directly below the offwidth crack with the tree at its base, in the upper level. Climb straight up and finish in the upper crack.

name: Hellish Move Jr.
description: Just left of the Access Route is a nasty little overhang. This line is just like Hellish Move, but on a smaller scale. Warning: the crux is probably dealing with the face just below the roof.

name: Horrific
description: Start in the middle of the west face, and climb up and follow a thin seam in the back of a dihedral to the ledge. Move right almost to the corner and finish by surmounting the overhanging top block.  Variation - Tanglefoot, 5.9: From the slanting ledge continue straight up the center of the overhanging upper face on good handholds.

name: North Crack
description: Climb 10 feet up the overhanging crack and continue up the easier blocky crack above it.

name: Popover
description: Begin just left of the center of the face, and climb up over a slight overhang and continue to the ledge. From the ledge, climb straight up the center of the overhanging upper block past a questionable buttonhead.  5.5 variation: Start on Popover, but finish by traversing right at the to the offwidth finish of Grisly.

name: Revelations
description: Start on the overhanging face left of North Crack. Muscle straight up the face without using either corner, or the large tree to the left of the route.

name: Ridge Route
description: Climb the southwest corner of the Open Bible to a large slanting ledge. Move left down the ledge to climb the short dihedral with and awkward but exhilarating layback finish.

name: Alpha
description: beta pending

name: And Agony
description: beta pending

name: Beta
description: beta pending

name: Digital Dexterity
description: beta pending

name: Face of Doom
description: beta pending

name: North Chimney (Flat on Your Back Crack)
description: Crack / chimney in the middle of the north side of Twin Sisters tower formation. Belayer is best at the very bottom near the trail - the climbing is 4th class / 5.easy at the beginning as you work your way up the ledges. Starts getting dicier as you approach the crack / chimney. Crux is when you first pull up into the chimney area and you're left to decide whether to try and wedge your way up the chimney or climb out onto the face. The hand holds are decent - the feet are a little trickier. Once you get over the chimney area its nice holds to pull yourself on top with some feet in the chimney to step up on.

name: Northeast Face
description: beta pending

name: Northwest Corner
description: beta pending

name: Ophidian
description: beta pending

name: Overhang
description: beta pending

name: Pedestal Crack
description: beta pending

name: Pedestal Face
description: beta pending

name: Snaky
description: A short exposed offwidth chimney climb. Start in Chimney top out on face.   Best used as access to north facing climbs such as Northeast (5.8).

name: Standard Route (Window Crack)
description: beta pending

name: Teeter
description: beta pending

name: West Face
description: beta pending

name: Air Head
description: This short but challenging climb follows the crack that starts at finger size and opens up to off-width hands, on the corner of the North face. Climb the crack using a layback with your feet inside the chimney.

name: Crack-a-Toe-a
description: Crack to the right of Java on the south face of Brother Buttress

name: Difficult Crack
description: This route is a challenge right from the start.  The crux is at the bottom where a short 7ft crack turns horizontal to meet up with the rest of the crack just to the right of it.  Using a nice jug that's deep in the crack and some clever smearing you can set yourself up nicely to make the transition between the two cracks.  After the crux is below you a series of well placed hand jams will give you success.

name: Front Stairs
description: Follow a series of ledges on the corner of the buttress.

name: North Face
description: Climb the chimney. The chockstone jammed in there will provide a bit of a challenge - it is easiest passed with a long stem across the chimney.

name: The Old and the Zestless
description: Struggle up and through the triangular niche set in the wall about ten feet up.

name: Sibling Rivalry
description: Climb the face around the corner from Dihedral Crack.

name: The Young and the Restless
description: Another short, but easier climb. Climb the hand crack all the way to the top.

name: Access Climb
description: This could possibly be classified as a moderate fourth class scamper.  Starts at the northeast corner and follows narrow ledges to the top of Indian Head Tower.

name: Bowline
description: This is a short route from the access area between the tower and main face of Indian Head climbing area.

name: Papoose
description: Short route on the south corner of the Indian Head main face.  Nice holds and simple to belay from top or bottom.

name: Quiver
description: North face climb up the Indian Head tower.  Starts in the center of the north side and follows straight up the center crack the angles right.  Leads to a grassy ledge before finishing the remaining 15' to top out.

name: Wrap-Around Route
description: This route starts at the west-northwest edge of the Indian Head Buttress and wraps around the south edge.

name: A Bee C
description: Climb up to the lone bush on this ramp, and then take the hand crack up to the cedar.

name: Bee Line
description: Double-shallow-roof route at the north end of the wall.

name: Buzz Off
description: Climb 10 feet into a seam, that opens up into a dihedral. When that gets too tough, step right around the corner.

name: Decapitator
description: Stay out of the depths of the chimney by stemming across the opening. Avoid the huge hanging blade that gives the climb its name.

name: Diabolical Dihedral
description: Climb 15 feet to the crumbly ledge. Follow the dihedral to the top.

name: Four Wings and Fly
description: Climb straight up the center of the face.

name: Nutcracker
description: Follow a small double-crack dihedral for 25 feet to an overhang. Dodge around the bulge on the left, and climb up 10 feet to a ledge. From the ledge, follow a seam directly above the lower crack to the top.

name: Ominous Extension
description: Climb up and left on a ramp. When you reach the dead end in the yellow, overhanging dihedral, traverse right on a small horizontal ledge to the center of a smooth face. Using and undercling and a very long reach, continue up the face to ledge holds and pockets with a mantel to the top.

name: Pollen on Buckets
description: Another hard face climb. The face overhangs, the pockets are small, and the footwork is dubious at best.

name: Pride of Cucamonga
description: A slightly overhanging face with several fine, roomy pockets. The only problem is that the pockets are just far enough apart to be brutal.

name: Shady Lane
description: Follow the dihedral to the top. Surprisingly solid rock. The route passes behind a cedar tree halfway up.

name: Six Hairy Legs
description: In the center of the wall is a yellow nose pointing Southwest. Climb the face just below this nose, and then tackle the nose itself.

name: TLC
description: Generous pockets and a few strategic face holds are spaced just right to stay on the "fun" side of the line.

name: Wise Crack
description: Climb up the blocky cleft to the find hand crack that starts 30 feet off the ground. Follow the crack for 15 feet and finish beneath the cedar branch.

name: Bombs Away
description: Face holds to a ledge 15 feet up, then up to the left and over a bulge, to more face climbing right of a small dihedral.

name: Bruce's Jam
description: Starts our as a thin seam, but opens up to hands and then fists.

name: Fear of Flying
description: Regarded by the guidebook authors as one of the finest in the park. Can be done in 2 pitches. Start at the extreme right of the yellow quarried rock. Up a sharp crack to a slanting roof.

name: Gravel Corner
description: beta pending

name: Hamilton's Arch
description: beta pending

name: Mountaineer's Route
description: This route used to be used to train for mountaineering objectives. Start at the lowest point of the wall, and scramble up ramps, ledges, and blocks.

name: Porky Pine's Solution
description: Begin in Bruce's Jam, then move left end of the ledge. Straight up from there, then rejoin Bruce's Jam to finish.

name: What For? Chimney
description: beta pending

name: Butter Fingers
description: Face holds up to a ledge. Angle up the seam system, then go for the top.

name: Butter Knife
description: Climb the crack. Well-protected lead.

name: Inch Worm
description: Follow a faint diagonal seam up and left, then move up and right to a small ledge. Continue straight up from the ledge.

name: Roundabout
description: Climb up pockets to the edge of the arch. Once above the roof, move left up the face.

name: Surprise Crack
description: Climb over a bulge to the crack. Crux consists of finger jams.

name: Way-Back Layback
description: Layback the dihedral. Very few face holds.

name: Green Savior
description: Climb the jutting outside corner to the left of Ode to Allen.  5.10 variation: Start on Green Savior, then traverse left into the vertical crack 12 feet above the roof. Climb to the top, using the crack and some good face holds.

name: Lace
description: Climb directly up the south-facing rippled face, just left of LM Crack. The route actually ends on the ledge 30 feet up, but a slight move to the right will allow one to pick up the upper jam crack of LM Crack.

name: LM Crack
description: Layback and jam the first 30 feet, power up and over the roof, and continue up the gravel-filled offwidth to the top.  5.9 variation -- The Mantle: begin with a challenging mantle onto the short ledge six feet off the ground, on the short face to the right of LM Crack. Then climb the face above to the roof of LM Crack.

name: No Sense of Decency
description: This climb follows the rotten 6th dihedral to the right from waterfall access. (Second dihedral North of Wide Glide.) Thrash your way up the dirty, loose, gnarly crack and claim the ascent!

name: Ode to Allen
description: This route lies in the first dihedral north of Wide Glide. Climb through 3 small roofs 25 feet up, and continue to the top.

name: Shake Down Street
description: This is a long, arching, overhanging crack in the dihedral. The crack starts in solid rock as thin fingers, then at 10 feet opens up into a nice hand crack. About 30 feet up, things get a bit dicey when the crack arches left into an area of looser rock.

name: Wide Glide
description: No idea on the grade... It has not been freed. Apparently it has been aided, but no grade was given.  This potential route attracts enormous attention because of the enticing nature of the fist crack running under its huge roof. Learn to climb hanging upside-down for about 15 feet and this wild line could be yours.

name: Dropzone
description: Start low on underclings and begin working up opposing side-pulls. Work through pockets and transition left into sloped horizontals. Top-out will likely be dirty, bring a brush and chalk bag up with you.

name: Gumby's Pizza
description: Short and sweet. Sit start on small pockets. Traverse right through large circle pocket to the arete.

name: Gumby's Pizza Direct
description: Start on Gumby's Pizza, move into large circle pocket and then fire straight up to good hold on lip.

name: Aqualung
description: Start in pockets and work up the water groove to bad slopers.

name: Foot Thief
description: High start in weird looking large jug. Head right.

name: Groovy Mike
description: Climb the obvious water groove located right in front of the tree.

name: Mrs. White
description: Fun warm up. Begin on good holds. Work up to big jug ledge and top out straight up.

name: The Mane
description: Climb the arete across from Nimbus boulder.

name: Nimbus
description: Climb the proud arete.

name: Black Magic Woman
description: Start on the large jug at the bottom and climb up the beautiful arete.

name: Cookie Monster
description: Climb the arete and be ready for the last move being the crux

name: Breast Melk
description: This route is top-ropeable from a tree but it should be done as a boulder if you have the means/ambition. Climb on mostly manufactured holds to a tricky crux on a slippery "S carving." A little extra effort cleaning the holds on rappel would be worth your time. Use the tree as your last hold for the airy mantle, and drink some breast melk for muscle recovery.Â

name: Two in the Crimp One in the Brimp
description: Mostly crimpy vertical face. Safest as a top rope, but if you want to send it as a boulder, be sure to clean the holds up top well. There's no clear crux on this route other than avoiding getting sand in your eyes up top.Â

name: Dan's Dihedral
description: Climb either crack or both using a variety of moves to reach the anchor

name: Dead Mouse
description: Originally, this route shared anchors withState Sponsored. As of 11/17/17 a new bolt has been added to the right of the anchor of State Sponsored. Clip it and continue to the top for a new anchor.      Pull through the hanging bloc face and reach better hold. Send the face until you reach the third bolt, then cut left, clip a bolt and continue to the top for a mantle to the anchor.    She found a dead mouse...

name: Dietsche Legacy Ladder
description: Begin climbing on the right side of the wall. Climb up and mantle on the ledge, clip in and traverse left. Follow the seam and mantle the top to reach the anchor.

name: Fire Chief Variation
description: Climb the left crack to the anchor    The First bolted route at Pere Marquette

name: Grafton Layback
description: Climb through large block jugs into a vertical flake system. Lay it back and work up and right into block jugs on the face. Mantle over the top and reach the anchor.

name: The Great River Road
description: P1: Begin on The Tallest Man and climb to the second bolt. Continue left clipping bolts as you continue to the Rapp Crack. Protect the crack with gear and work onto the traverse ledge of Dietsche Legacy Ladder. Continue up to the 4th bolt and then traverse left on good/large holds and continue to the anchor of Dan's Dihedral. Belay your party to you from this point.     P2: Climb left using the anchors of the Lucky Strike Pillar for protection. Continue by using all of the anchors from Hornbein's Wall until you reach the anchor of Great Green Chute. Belay your party to you from here.     P3: Climb left and protect the corner of Horbein's Wall with a cam. Continue protecting yourself by clipping the anchors of the Community Effort Wall. Stop on the ledge at the anchor of Feeding the Hungry for a comfortable belay and bring your party across.      P4: Due to a large precarious rock (the has potential to eventually fall) down-climb to the ground and walk left along the actual balcony of Ryan's Balcony. Build an anchor using the two bolts of 50 Shades of Grey to bring your partners across.     P5: From the above stated belay, continue left clipping bolts from Vista and The Father Gift to climb into the dihedral corner of Spicy Guacamole. Climb up the face and work left at bolt three onto RIver Night & Flashlights. Continue left protecting with the anchors and build a belay at the anchor of the Hespen Arete.     P6: Climb left protecting with the anchors of the routes on the Wall of Wild Things. Build an anchor on the anchor of Sleeping Indian. Bring your party across, and once together. Rappell off the anchor to the ground.

name: Keep Up Youth!
description: Climb the crack to the anchor

name: Rapp Crack AKA Numero Uno
description: climb the rightward crack to the anchor

name: The Ring Neck
description: Pull through the hanging bloc and gain better stone. Ease your way through tricky moves and eventually mantle over the top to reach the anchor.

name: State Sponsored
description: Climb the the short hanging bloc section to reach the dihedral face. Begin up, and eventually reach and pull around the right. Climb the last section and reach the anchor

name: The Tallest Man
description: Pull through the hanging bloc and begin up the face. Lay it back and hike though the arching flake to eventually mantle over the top and reach the anchor

name: Catfish & Bottlenecks
description: Pull a few moves and press out the crux early on. Enjoyable climbing leads to the anchor

name: Cocktail
description: Climb straight up and angle towards the arete on the right. Pull on good holds and sink your tips into some pockets to eventually gain purchase on good block jugs then climb to the finish

name: Piasa Pusher
description: Begin in the dihedral and climb up 2 bolts. Cut left to a horizontal ledge and push it out. Fun climbing from here to the anchor

name: Fin Inn
description: Climb the  large arching flake utilizing stemming and jams. Pull the fin at the top and reach the anchor

name: Great Green Chute
description: Fight your way through the wide crack and protect when you can. The higher you climb the more it relaxes. Upon reaching the top tread your rope into the ram horns.

name: The Loading Dock
description: Send the arching flake protecting when needed. Plug gear into the horizontal before the anchor

name: Oyster Bar
description: Climb the crack using lybacks and jams to reach the anchor

name: Peace of Quiche
description: Climb the crack using a variety of stems, lybacks, jams

name: American Red Cross
description: Start out on very moderate moves. After utilizing the jug to clip the 2nd bolt fire out to a right hand crimp. Left foot placement is crucial here. Do a mini gaston to a positive yet painful finger lock. Do a left hand foot match to stand up then clip. Take a good couple breaths and finish it out on slabby 10+ terrain to a fun mantle. The locks and holds can be sharp so if you have delicate fingers stay off.

name: Feeding The Hungry
description: Begin under the first bolt and work up into ledge. from here use the split in the ledge and work left to a side pull and move your way back right and work up the seam to a jug. Continue up to shared anchors with Ice Cream Social.Huge thanks to Bill, Ryan, Nikki, and Molly for helping to clean this wall up.

name: Food Stamps
description: Climb up and right clipping two bolts, then mantle over a small ledge. Clip the small bolt on the ledge (as a directional) and continue to the anchor from here.Â

name: Ice Cream Social
description: Climb the thin crack, protecting when necessary, to eventually reach a two bolt anchor

name: Parenthood
description: Climb up the face and layback on good, but sharp holds.

name: 50 Shades Of Grey
description: Not yet bolted. From the ledge its the left most bolted short route

name: The Father's Gift
description: Thank Ryan Richardson for this one. Strong contender for best route of Pere Marquette.    Climb the well protected face beginning with underlings and side pulls. Stand up on the small ledge and make a long reach to good pockets on the right side of the bolt line. Make the clip and begin using the holds on the left again. From here follow the rail and continue up and left to the anchor.

name: Gillete Arete
description: Climb the arete using both the arete and face holds to reach the anchor

name: Toothbrush Crack
description: Climb the thin crack in the center of the wall

name: Vista
description: Climb up the ledge and move and grab a nice jug to position yourself on the upper face. Pull hard through a series of shallow pockets and eventually use both sides of the arete to reach the anchor    Note: potentially the best scenic views at the park

name: Fine Line
description: The beginning is a worker. Especially in warm conditions. Once standing on the ledge prepare yourself for sharp yet very positive holds to a jug. Shake it out and work those feet through a mini crux to the chains. Fine line indeed. :-)

name: Hespen Arete
description: Begin up the left side of the aerie using good holds, eventually work you way to the aerie and use both sides to reach the top

name: River Nights & Flashlights
description: Pull on edges and face holds moving up and right to reach the anchor

name: Spicy Guacamole
description: Climb your way between the two walls, stemming, and eventually reach the anchor

name: Cricket Crack
description: Climb the crack jamming and laying back when you can. Bolted anchor at the top

name: The Luna Moth
description: Scramble over the section of hanging bloc and clip the bolt. Head and through the right wing of the Luna Moth and reach the anchor

name: Native Crack
description: Climb the wide crack directly left of Sleeping Indian

name: Reptilia
description: For the very large lizard that appeared during bolting    Begin at the same spot as Cricket Crack and make your way up and left. Pull through the face and gain access to the anchor

name: Sleeping Indian
description: Another great climb found by Ryan Richardson. Begin in the crack and work your way up to the first bolt. From here work you way to the right and side pull against a crack to eventually an undercling to stand up and work you way towards the top.

name: Welcome to the Glitter Side
description: Crawl over the hanging bloc section and balance into a layback, stick it out and balance your way to the anchor

name: Apex Predator
description: Follow the thin crack to the anchor

name: The Eaglet
description: Clip the first two bolts on Leaving the Nest, and continue left up the crack.

name: Empty Nest
description: Climb the crack while either jamming the crack or stemming the two walls

name: Fledgling
description: Climb the crack protecting when necessary

name: Hawkeye
description: Dig through the thin seam, placing gear when necessary to reach the anchor

name: Leaving the Nest
description: Climb through easy terrain to the ledge.  Move right to small face holds and finish to the left of the arete.

name: Scavenger
description: Start up the face and work your way into the crack system. Layback and stem to the anchor

name: Where Eagles Dare
description: Navigate your way through the start to the small roof bulge. Take a deep breath and punch your way through the solid limestone crux sequences. This one will keep you on your toes until you clip the chains.

name: Anchors Away!
description: Climb the short face pulling on large block jugs and and old drill seam to reach the top

name: Giant Steps
description: Climb the oversized stairs to reach the anchor

name: Global Worming
description: Corner to the right of Joeys Route. As of now shares the anchors with Joeys route which leads to a traverse at the end. The climbing is easy but there is no protection on the traverse- hence the PG rating.

name: Joeys Route
description: Climb up and right through the dihedral, clipping as you go and eventually reach the chains

name: The Mad Ferryman
description: Begin at the upside down stair feature and climb the slab. Eventually make your way up and left

name: Meadow's
description: Climb the crack using lybacks and jams

name: Mississippi Side Step
description: Developed by Austin Cooling    Pull on small holds to eventually reach the anchor

name: Riverboat Gambler
description: Layback the thin seam and eventually use face holds to reach the anchor

name: Boy Scout Route
description: Climb the featured slab to reach the chains

name: Cody's First Lead
description: Climb the slab using edges to reach the chains at the top

name: N.A.R.B.
description: Climb the face using small edges and a thin crack to reach the top

name: N.L.C.
description: Climb the crack

name: Scout's Dihedral
description: Climb the dihedral and use the same chains at N.L.C.

name: Training Wheels
description: Start up the ramp and climb through the blocky section to reach the anchor

name: Water Wings
description: Another good one for a young climber

name: Cool Up
description: Start with hands matched low on the small ledge about two feet off the ground, and top out directly above after a few easy moves.

name: Hang a Louie
description: Starting with hands matched in the widest opening of the horizontal crack to the left of the tree (start is about four feet to the left of the tree, and four feet off the ground), traverse to the left, past the big vertical crack and then the smaller one, until you top out on the ledge just to the left of the smaller crack, about five feet off the ground.

name: Hang a Randy
description: Starting with hands matched on the ledge (about five feet off the ground, just to the left of the two vertical cracks), traverse to the right, past the small vertical crack and then the bigger one, until you finish with your hands matched in the widest opening of the horizontal crack to the left of the tree (hand finish is about four feet to the left of the tree, and four feet off the ground).

name: Left Open Project
description: This is an open project that someone should go claim. Â Sit start and follow the technical line straight up the face.Â

name: Open Arete Project
description: Begin low on undercling feature and climb straight up the arete

name: Open Arete Project No.2
description: Climb the arete while starting low

name: Thanks, But No Thanks
description: Start on two hand rail jug and work up right on crack.

name: V1/2 crack
description: Ascend the small but deep right facing crack. Down climb to the right.

name: Warm Down
description: Start with hands matched on rectangular rock jutting out of the face about three feet off the ground, and top out directly above after a few easy moves.

name: Blow Away
description: The line left of Truckin'. Start matched in the jug just down and left of the slopey rail of truckin. Move left then up.Â

name: Fire on the Mountain
description: Another great line up the fin. Start on the obvious starting block down low and climb the blank looking face. Top out. Don't grab the giant hollow horn jug at the top.Â

name: Sunshine Daydream
description: A Sunshine Daydream. Don't be an idiot.Â

name: Truckin'
description: Perhaps one of the best boulder problems out here. Start matched on the bottom of the slopey left facing rail. The small detached block at the bottom is off. Gain the groove out right and surmount. Really unsure of the grade..Â

name: Althea
description: Grades? Pretty darn cool one. Left hand on the slopey crimp, right on the shallow pocket/ divot under the right facing rail. Top out onto ledge. Down climb or traverse left until you can WALK to the top of the block. Walk off near the wide entrance of the hallway. Â This route could possibly go starting left hand lower on the hollow sounding edge, much harder.Â

name: Dingus
description: Start right hand on the low sculpted pinch and left around the arete. get no hands on the ledge above and down climb.Â

name: Missile Tits
description: Start on the two jug pockets on the left side of the overhang. Work up and right. Top out over the prow. Walk down the right side of the boulder, there's nice steps.Â

name: Seamless
description: A real shame this one isn't longer. Start on the in-cut crimps at mid height. Proceed. Pretty sure the easiest way down is to down climb the problem.Â

name: The Fool's Progress
description: Start on the kind of sandy block in the back of the overhang. The rock quality immediately gets better. Make a big move to the lip, and a few more moves to top out onto the ledge. Also not sure about the grade of this one.Â

name: The Fridge
description: As fun as it looks. left hand in pocket under the rail, right in the undercling pinch. Grab the jug on the top to finish, or test your odds with the mud and leaves that lie above...Â

name: Hayduke Lives
description: No idea about the grade.. Start low on two pockets in the middle of the wall, climb up then left, topping out the center of the prow. Scoot right asap on the top out to avoid mud and leaves. Walk off right.Â

name: Hell in a Bucket project
description: Try to climb the huge awesome overhang. Supurb movement. Top outs loose mud, but a possible escape ledge exists..Â

name: My friend Garlick
description: Start right hand on the arete pinch at mid height, left way down low on the in cut left facing crimp. Top out, a fun one.Â

name: Shawnee Solitaire
description: The first problem I climbed out here and one of the best problems so far, even being a drop off. Start right hand in the scoop, left on the crimp. Fire to the pinch. a few more moves will take you to the jug above the overhang. Drop. Kind of left right and center variations to get to the finish, all around the same grade. This would be a four star boulder problem if the to-be top out wasn't certain death by mud. Unfortunately I am discovering this to often be wet.Â Â

name: A Dedication to Andy Boone
description: Start low in the back of the cave, pull perfect hand jams out the cave.Â

name: Arete Project
description: Climb the arete

name: Flatty
description: Low start on a flat jug and work your way to the top from here.Â

name: Green Flies
description: Start to the right of the Highball Project, traverse to the right and then go up.

name: Head Lock
description: Jump start to a huge pinch. Climb up the blunt arete. According the the guide book, the was the first boulder problem climbed at Pounds Lake

name: HIghball Project
description: Project that climbs through the cave.Â

name: Ivy
description: Start low and climb up the face

name: Patty Cakes Left
description: Climb up and left

name: Patty Cakes Right
description: Climb up and right

name: Pin Scar Race
description: Climb the thin crack with the natural pin scar

name: Project
description: Open project located on the short clifflineÂ

name: Prow Project
description: Climb the prow feature

name: Shattered
description: Sit start on The Zebra, then traverse up and right.Â

name: Zebra's in America
description: Traverse into The Zebra

name: The Zebra
description: Sit Start on a jug, reach up to some slopey jugs. Then, fire up to a large sloper. One of the best problems at Pounds Lake according to Matt Bliss.Â

name: The Bull Project
description: Sit start with right hand on a tiny, rounded edge and left hand on an almost non existent hold. Pull up off the ground and then throw to a big, slopey pinch

name: Cheek Project
description: Climb the left cheek of the "butt" feature

name: Elephant Butt Hair
description: Sit start on a jug that has some flex to it. Throw left to a "butt" feature, and work your way up from here.Â

name: Greenie Mantel
description: Climb the boulder problem left of the Cheek Project. If you climb straight up it is harder then if you angle up and left.Â

name: The Leprechaun
description: Sit start with a right hand on a sloper, and a left on an undercling. Bring a brush. This rig has cool moves, but is probably dirty.Â

name: Mantel Project
description: Do the Mantel on the South side of the boulder

name: Bath Tub Gin
description: Several feet left of Creal Billies, sit start on pinch pocket & go straight up.

name: Eternal Sunshine
description: Sit start on big layback, move to slopey shelf. Head right on big pinches & top out on shelf.

name: The Seam
description: Stand start in the obvious seam & top out. A VERY hard project exists starting this much lower on the seam deep in the cave.

name: Year of the Renegade
description: In the cave, jump start to obvious horn like feature. Climb out right to pockets on the roof.

name: [Redacted]
description: Start same as Screaming Eagle but climb out right. Long move to sharp hold & top out.

name: Screaming Eagle
description: Sit start on rail a few feet right of the arete & head up left. Follow good holds to fun topout. Defintely a Roost classic.

name: Chuck Norris
description: Perhaps THE classic hard problem of The Roost. Sit down start The Oriole. Left in pocket, right low undercling for full value.Â

name: The Gobbler
description: On the back of the Oriole boulder, start on left side of Southern Illinois's biggest sloper. Climb out to arete, follow it up staying on the right side.

name: Life on Mars
description: sit start. move through a few sharp crimps to a jug then bust a big move to a ledge.

name: Life on Mars high start
description: Bypass the first move, starting on the two thin crimps. Make a small move and set up for the world class huck.Â

name: Lip Traverse
description: Pretty fun little traverse, albeit a little sandy. Decent warm up for the area. Start standing on the right side of the Oriole Boulder traverse to the end of the Oriole and topout.

name: The Oriole
description: Takes its name from the bright orange coloring of the sandstone. High start on underclings, throw to jug. Classic.

name: Unknown
description: Start standing on two side pulls. Do a couple wide compression moves on sloper sidepulls then top out. A harder sit start could be possible.

name: Ring of Fire
description: Ring of Fire starts on a large pedestal, climb up it and through the roof using large pockets and crimps to the crux finish at the lip.

name: Booze and Burritos
description: Right above staircase, right of a small water drainage, in bend. Tops out on rock before it turns to top soil above.Â

name: Stagnant H2O
description: Right of metal staircase, up distinctive water drainage (dry unless it just rained). Start as Booze and Burritos and traverse over.Â

name: Actions Speak Louder Than Words
description: Around corner & 10 feet right of a small cave

name: Easy Does It
description: First boulder problem right of small roof.Â

name: This May Cause Cancer
description: Route straight up from small cave before curve. Top out on top ledge.Â

name: Sinnissippi Park Grand Traverse
description: This is a 160', 8" band of white chert running 6'- 10' above the ground, on a sunny south-facing cliff of chossy limestone. This is mostly a traverse. Handholds are on the shelf the chert lies on. Footholds are wherever one finds them. Bouldering and climbing may become safer as the wall looses it's chossiness. Chalk is NOT required for this route.

name: Unknown 1
description: Climb through a bulge and up a face to an anchor

name: Unknown 2
description: Climb through the protruding rib feature and up a slightly overhug face.Â

name: Unknown 3
description: Climb up a bludge and through the overhung face

name: Unknown 4
description: Climb the face

name: Unknown 5
description: Climb the featured faceÂ

name: Unknown 6
description: Climb up a face, through a small buldge, then up and right to the anchor
